<HEADLINE> Microsoft Invests in Canada's Cable Television </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. software giant Microsoft
Corp. invests 600 million Canadian dollars (about 408 million U.S.
dollars) into Canada's largest cable television company Rogers
Communication Inc..
</P>
<P>
The two sides have signed a series of agreements on the
development of television into a two-way appliance to communicate,
conduct E-commerce and watch television programs and movies.
</P>
<P>
Rogers, which has about 2.3 million cable customers, is
expecting a phased roll-out next year, as it has already licensed
Microsoft to support at least 1 million "set-top boxes," according
to business reports published here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The "box," which will be the biggest change for consumers, is a
small but powerful computer that will allow the user to record
shows, use the Internet and allow old analog televisions to
receive digital broadcasting signals.
</P>
<P>
Ted Rogers, chief executive officer of Rogers, was quoted as
saying, "We intend to ally ourselves with the best, most
knowledgeable people in the world so that we can build the finest
systems here in Canada." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
