<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Trio Case Postponed Again in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The trial of three Americans
arrested in March in the Zimbabwean capital on suspicion of
carrying dangerous weapons was postponed Tuesday for the second
time by the High Court to July 19 to give the state time to
prepare its case.
</P>
<P>
The case had been postponed from Monday to Tuesday because the
prosecutor handling it was ill.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Attorney General Andrew Chigovera told Justice George
Smith that the case should be postponed for at least two weeks as
the state needed to get a new prosecutor to study the case.
</P>
<P>
Justice Smith, however, agreed with the defence led by Advocate
Chris Anderson that the time of two weeks was too long considering
the suffering faced by the accused at one time in prison.
</P>
<P>
Chigovera argued that one week was too short because the state
needed time to establish whether the three were carrying out
genuine missionary work in the Democratic Republic of Congo where
arms were discovered in the house they were staying.
</P>
<P>
He also said if the state had to get a new prosecutor, the
prosecutor would need time to study evidence from at least 20
witnesses and would also go through evidence from pictures, videos
and films.
</P>
<P>
Chigovera said the case had attracted international attention
that its outcome would reflect against the Zimbabwean judiciary
system if it was not properly handled.
</P>
<P>
The three Americans, George Blanchard (35), Joseph Pettijohn
(34) and John Dixon (35), were arrested on March 8 at the Harare
International Airport after they were allegedly found in
possession of a large assortment of arms of war, including
automatic rifles and ammunition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
