<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Emir Appoints New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah appointed on Tuesday a 16-member new
government with nine new faces following last week's Cabinet
resignation.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Jaber made the appointment based on a proposal
presented by Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad
Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah, the official news agency KUNA reported.
</P>
<P>
There are still six members of the royal Al-Sabah family
who were named in the new cabinet. Former ministers of
foreign affairs, defense and interior, all senior members of
the ruling family, all retained their key portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah also remained in his
post. However, Minister of Finance and Minister of Communications
Sheikh Al Salem Al-Ali Al-Sabah was replaced by Ahmad Abdallah
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, a banker.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of State for National Assembly (parliament)
Affairs Mohammad Deifallah Sharar succeeded Abdul Aziz Al-Dahil
as Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Other new comers are Minister of Justice Saad Jassem Youssef
Al-Hashel, Minister of Information Saad Mohammad Bin Teflah
Al-Ajmi, Minister of Health Mohammad Ahmad Al-Jarallah and
Minister of Education and Higher Education Youssef Hamad
Al-Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Former foreign undersecretary Suleiman Majid Al-Shahin was
named Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, the only
newly-established post.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Works is parliament member (MP) Eid
Hathal Saud Al-Rashidi, the only lawmaker who was selected in
the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of Health Adel Khalid Al-Subih changed his
post as Minister of Electricity and Water, Minister of State for
Housing Affairs and Minister of Awqaf and Islamic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Bteihan Al-Dweihees replaced Ali Moussa Al-Moussa as
Minister of Planning and Minister of State for Administrative
Development Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Wahab Mohammad Al-Wazzan was named as the new Minister
of Commerce and Industry, and Minister of Labor and Social
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's last cabinet resigned under the constitution on July
4, after final results of the country's parliament elections
were officially announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
