<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Population Council Committed to Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's National Population
Council (NPC) said Tuesday that women empowerment, girl-child
education and unsafe abortion would be the core of its program for
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
These, according to NPC, form part of the world population
agenda formulated by the International Conference for Population
and Development for the 21st Century, the Ghana News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Accra, capital of Ghana,
Richard Turkson, executive secretary of NPC, said these could be
achieved through strengthening linkages with government
institutions and non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to
intensify public education.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the Council's strategies, Turkson said partnerships
with the public sector, donor agencies and NGOs have already
produced a number of important policy guidelines for population
control.
</P>
<P>
They include the medium-term health strategy, national
reproductive health policy, draft national adolescent
reproductive health and national communication strategy.
</P>
<P>
Turkson said there has been significant progress in
implementing these policies which is demonstrated in the
enactment by parliament of the Children's Bill.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, there has been a sharp decline in fertility rates
from 6.5 children per woman in 1960 to 4.5 in 1998, while the use
of modern contraceptives has improved from five percent in 1981
to 13 percent as of now.
</P>
<P>
 However, he said, the successful implementation of the
revised national population policy leading to further reduction
in fertility and an improved quality of life would depend on
massive attitudinal and behavioral change.
</P>
<P>
"This, of course, cannot, in the nature of things, happen
overnight but determined efforts are being made to lay a firm
foundation now," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
