<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. Plans to Create Trade Office in Thessaloniki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen Tuesday said in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki that
Washington intended to set up a commercial bureau in the city with
the aim of participating in the Balkan reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with his Greek counterpart, Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, Cohen, who arrived Tuesday afternoon for an
official two-day visit, praised Greece for the indispensable role
Athens has played in the pacification of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the northern Greek city would
play a major part in the reconstruction of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) leaders decided last month to base its
agency for the reconstruction of the Balkans in Thessaloniki, the
largest city in northern Greece.
</P>
<P>
Tsohazopoulos described Cohen's visit as "political" as it
coincided with the selection of Thessaloniki as the headquarters
of the Balkan reconstruction agency, and with the relevant efforts
of the EU and the United States.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two ministers discussed the common
effort for the stabilization of the Balkan region, the situation
in the Middle East and the Mediterranean, bilateral cooperation in
tackling terrorism and the modernization of the Greek armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Cohen will meet in Athens with Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis and Foreign Minister George Papandreou.
</P>
</TEXT>
