<HEADLINE> Khatami Warns Against Unrest in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
on Tuesday warned that his government will seriously deal with any
riot against the country's interests and government's policies.
</P>
<P>
"Any riot is against the interest of the Islamic system and the
nation as well as the government's slogans and policies," Khatami
told the state-run television after an extraordinary meeting of
the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC).
</P>
<P>
However, he said that his government is committed to peaceful
behavior and avoiding violence and is trying to deal as
peacefully as possible with the current violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's warning came as more clashes erupted between Iranian
anti-riot police and several thousand demonstrators protesting the
recent police crackdown on the Tehran University students on
Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA), several
groups of people staged sporadic and unorganized rallies at
various spots in Tehran Tuesday, the 6th day of student protests
to the police crackdown.
</P>
<P>
In defiance of the SNSC's ban on illegal gatherings, several
groups of masked demonstrators armed with clubs and stones clashed
with rival groups that held other types of make-shift weapons,
IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
The student protests have turned to be the worst unrest in Iran
since the Islamic revolution in 1979, arousing concerns of Iranian
leaders about possible uprising against the Islamic system.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami stressed that his government is against any
violence and is serious about security for the country and the
people.
</P>
<P>
Expressing apology to the Iranian nation for the unrest during
the past six days, he called on the Iranian people to distance
themselves from the unrest and to give a free hand to the
government to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
Terming the police assault on student's hostels as "
extraordinarily bitter," the Iranian reformist president promised
to seriously follow up the case.
</P>
<P>
A committee formed by protesting students on Tuesday night
also denounced the unrest in the country and stated that the
students will suspend their protests until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The students will never confirm sabotage and riot in any
forms," the committee said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee restated the students' demand calling
for dismissal of the Iranian police chief Brigadier General
Hedayat Lotfian.
</P>
<P>
It also demanded the transfer of the police commanding
authorities to the Interior Ministry and dismissal of hard-liners
from the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
