<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, July 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's conservative-dominated police on Tuesday broke
up a rally protesting against police crackdown on students, and
arrested a number of people, the Islamic Iranian News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, labeled by IRNA as "rioters," threw stones and
clubs at the policemen who were trying to disperse them in front
of the main gate of the Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
But the agency did not say how many protesters took part in the
demonstration and how many of them were
arrested.(BC-Iran-Protests-Clashes)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Tuesday
that progress in the peace negotiations with the Palestinians may
trigger new terrorist attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with senior Israeli military and security
officials, Barak said some extremist groups such as Hamas may be
encouraged by the momentum in the peace process to carry out
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Barak asked all Israeli security agencies to remain alert and
be prepared for countering such possible
attacks.(BC-Israel-Terrorism)
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus and Greece have agreed to lift objections to
Turkey's bid to join the European Union (EU), Cyprus Foreign
Minister Ioannis Kasoulides told the Athens News Agency (ANA)
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of Greek Foreign Ministry Yiannos Kranidiotis
said on Monday that it will be preferable if Turkey meets the
requirements set by EU leaders to be designated as an EU candidate.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Greece will allow Turkey to become an EU
candidate on two conditions: firstly, Cyprus' accession to the EU
would go ahead unhindered by a political solution to the Cyprus
issue being a prerequisite; secondly, a public statement of
solidarity from the EU on the Aegean. (BC-Cyprus-Greece-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Knesset (parliament) Tuesday passed
the first reading of a bill that would allow the expansion of the
new government from 18 to 24 ministers.
</P>
<P>
Since all ruling parties have agreed to the government
expansion while signing coalition agreements with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, the first reading of the bill was approved by a large
majority.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-nine members of the 120-seat Knesset voted for the bill,
while 38 were against and 13 abstained.(BC-Israel-Government
Expansion)

13/07/99 19:52 GMT

NNNN
04:01 04:02 g # PAB
</P>
