<HEADLINE> Human Rights High on OAU Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A report, presented to the three-day OAU summit, was concluded
by the OAU experts and adopted by Council of Ministers during the
70th ordinary session which met on July 6-10 here in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Though some "tangible results" have been witnessed in human
rights protection, the report said, more efforts must be made in
order to reach the final objective.
</P>
<P>
The enhancement of democratic values in Africa through the
choice of governments as well as freedom of the press are two
evidences of the human rights protection in Africa, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, more efforts should be exerted for the struggle against
poverty in addition to resolving internal conflicts peacefully, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the role of the non-governmental organizations
(NGOs) in defending human rights cases, experts also paid a great
deal of attention to women, children and refugees.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the necessary means likely to help in the struggle
against human rights violations, the report highlighted that at
least 15 states have not ratified the African charter on the
rights of children.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, human rights violations in Africa are
mainly due to racism, post-colonialism, different forms of
slavery, poverty, ignorance, diseases, religious intolerance,
internal conflicts, debt, bad management and corruption.
</P>
<P>
The monopoly of power, the lack of judicial and press autonomy,
border conflicts in addition to the political shakings and
disturbances and terrorism are also listed as roots for the
violations.
</P>
<P>
The report prescribed that strategies to reinforce human rights
 protection should be on both the continental and national levels.
</P>
<P>
The protocol dealing with the creation of an African court for
human rights should be ratified as soon as possible by all the
countries in the continent while closer cooperation with the
United Nations institutions and other organizations, the report
urged.
</P>
<P>
On the national level, it called on each of the OAU member
state to be aware of its respective duties deriving from the
African human rights charter and other additional pertinent
treaties for coordinating its efforts in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Equitable and fair opportunities for all Africans without sex
difference and the respect of the principle of fair geographical
representation were also stressed in the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
