<HEADLINE> Algerian President Calls for African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, who is newly appointed the head of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), spelt out here Tuesday the principal factors
for the reinforcement of the industrial strategies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the sponsorship groups for the Alliance of
African Industrialization, Bouteflika said Africa is characterized
by its "weak manufacturing items in comparison with the world
production," because of the stagnation of its industrializing
process and the absence of adequate industrial strategies of the
adjusting structural programs.
</P>
<P>
"Algeria is bringing its full support to the construction of an
 effective and strong alliance for the industrialization of our
continent," he said, adding that to reach this objective, Africa
needs to find expert human resources and important managing
potentials that could supply the necessary conditions to boost
economies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika recalled that the Abidjan Declaration of 1996
established strong lines which define the type of correlation
between the national and local strategies in order to ensure the
ability of competition on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Pragmatic measures should be taken in the second decade for the
 industrial development in Africa, the president said, adding that
hard work is needed for the industrialization of Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
