<HEADLINE> Albright to Travel to Mideast on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright is planning to visit the Middle East early in
August following President Bill Clinton's meeting with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak in an effort to help push forward the
peace process, the State Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She is expected to stop in Damascus for talks with Syrian
President Hafez Assad, meet in Jerusalem with Barak and Foreign
Minister David Levy, and to meet with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat in Palestinian-held territory as well as other Arab
leaders.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Albright, once
keeping away from the Middle East conflict, is now ready to devote
much of her time to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I know the secretary has already made a decision that she's
prepared to spend a substantial amount of her time working on
the Middle East peace process in the coming months," Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Asked what role the United States would play once the peace
process was revived in the Middle East, Rubin said Washington
would help build confidence between Israel and the Arab nations
and hope the parties concerned would lead the way in building
peace.
</P>
<P>
"And we are there more for a confidence-building and
intermediary role than a negotiating one," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
