<HEADLINE> UNICEF Appeals for Food Aid to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has appealed to the world community to provide
urgent assistance to Ethiopians affected by food shortage, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Although the UNICEF is appealing for other forms of emergency
assistance, we must underscore the importance of the food needs
being met.
</P>
<P>
"The other interventions cannot succeed on their own without
adequate caloric intake," UNICEF emergency officer Bob Mccarthy
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF portion of the appeal covers interventions proven to
save lives in emergencies. These include supplementary feeding
for over 95,000 children under five and 71,000 pregnant and
lactating women, measles vaccination, expanding access to clean
water and supplying blankets to the most vulnerable, a UNICEF
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, which supports one issued by the Ethiopian
government's disaster prevention and preparedness commission, also
covers 208,000 metric tons of food aid, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ethiopia appealed to donor community to provide
360,000 tons of emergency food aid to 4.6 million victims of food
shortage.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that parts of Ethiopia failed to have enough
rain in small rainy season from February to May this year, which
has caused the grain shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
