<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- In cooperation with the United States, Lebanon
seeks to develop a high-tech zone in Beirut over the coming two
years.
</P>
<P>
The proposed zone, similar to those in the United States,
Mexico and Malaysia, will be the first of its kind in the Middle
East, the Arabic daily Al-Hayat on Tuesday quoted Chairman of the
Arab General Institution for Investment Promotion in Lebanon
Youssif Shokair as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agency for Development and Trade granted Lebanon
174,000 U.S. dollars to fund the feasibility studies on the
project, Shokair added.
</P>
<P>
The zone will attract global firms that are specialized in
partial or full manufacture of computer hardware chips and CDs as
well as in electrical industries such as TV sets.
</P>
<P>
It will also cover various services in the video-clip,
advertisement and studio industries, Shokair said.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria has decided to impose controls on the
export of all kinds of olive oil as from early 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local economists attributed the move to poor canning style
that led to the decline of Syrian olive oil exports, Al-Alam
Al-Youm newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The production of Tunisia's oil and gas went up in
1998 by 4.4 percent to reach 5.6 million tons compared to that of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The production of crude oil rose from 3.8 million tons in 1997
to 3.9 million tons last year while the gas production went up from
1.59 million tons to 1.74 million tons in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The increase was attributed to the exploitation of 26 oil
fields, four of which started operation last year, Al-Alam Al-Youm
newspaper on Tuesday quoted an official economic survey as saying.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Minister of Oil Amir Mohammed Rashid said his
country is willing to have trade exchanges with other Arab Gulf
states, noting that there was a tendency to expand such exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Iraq gives priority in its trade dealings with the Arab
countries that account for 50 percent of Iraq's foreign trade
volume, Al-Alam Al-Youm newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Gulf States were awarded contracts involving more than
400 million U.S. dollars under the U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the sixth phase of the deal, Iraq singed with Saudi firms
contracts worth 150 million U.S. dollars, said the minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
