<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian Government Denies Allegations of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The government of Burundi
Tuesday expressed dissatisfaction with reports being circulated by
rebel groups that the recent killings in the capital Bujumbura
were carried out with the knowledge and consent of the military
rulers in power.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement signed by Burundi's Minister for Peace
Process Ambroise Niyonsaba and the Deputy Speaker Augustin
Njojibwami said that the remarks were inflammatory and could put
the ongoing talks in a very delicate situation.
</P>
<P>
"All these remarks are undue and unfounded," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
They urged the rebels to make responsible remarks and work for
reconstruction in the war-torn central African country.
</P>
<P>
The statement, released from Arusha, northern Tanzania, also
reaffirmed the Burundian government's determination to pursue
peace.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, ethnically divided between minority Tutsis and
majority Hutus, has been going through a civil war since the
country's first elected Hutu president was murdered by Tutsi
troops in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
A new round of peace talks aimed at ending the civil war
started last Thursday in Arusha, bringing together the government
and Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
Rebel groups such as the National Council for the Defense of
Democracy (CNDD) and Party of Hutu People's Liberation
(PALEPEHUTU), also denied that they were involved in the recent
killings of more than 30 people, and last Sunday's attack which
killed 11 people, including eight who were burnt to death.
</P>
<P>
The rebels condemned the killings and challenged the Burundian
government to arrest those who were responsible for the killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
