<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Hits 19 Dollars for 1st Time in 20 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Brent crude oil prices hit 19 U.S.
dollars a barrel for the first time in 20 months Tuesday as close
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) adherence
to output cuts continued to strengthen market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Brent for August delivery broke above the psychological 19.00
U.S. dollars barrer to trade at 19.03 U.S. dollars Tuesday
afternoon on London's International Petroleum Exchange, its
highest value since November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have jumped nearly 2 U.S. dollars in the past two
weeks, the latest leg in a recovery which has taken Brent up from
lows of less than 10 U.S. dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
The latest push to the rally came after a Gulf official said
Tuesday that Saudi Arabia wanted cast iron proof of a full market
recovery before the OPEC would consider easing export limits, a
Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC compliance with the supply curbs in the last two months
has reached 85-90 percent of targeted levels, according to Reuters
surveys.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts expect surplus stockpiles to be erased by the end
of September, leaving the market exposed to higher prices during
the peak northern hemisphere winter demand season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
