<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Passes First Reading on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Tuesday passed the first reading of a bill that would allow the
expansion of the new government from 18 to 24 ministers.
</P>
<P>
Since all ruling parties have agreed to the government
expansion while signing coalition agreements with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, the first reading of the bill was approved by a large
majority.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-nine members of the 120-seat Knesset voted for the bill,
while 38 were against and 13 abstained.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who took office last week, has initiated the bill in an
effort to accommodate the large coalition in his cabinet, which
has the support of 75 Knesset members. And the bill was approved
by Barak's cabinet unanimously on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition Likud Party has accused Barak of wasting
the public funds. The former Likud finance minister Meir Sheetrit
has claimed that the government expansion would cost 400 million
shekels (97.56 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
During a stormy debate on the bill before Tuesday's voting,
Haim Ramon, Minister in Prime Minister's Office, responded that
the bill would only cost 9 million shekels (2.2 million dollars)
annually.
</P>
<P>
Ramon, who cited a letter from Treasury budget director David
Milgrom, said the opposition had made a gross exaggeration and
that "they could not be taken seriously."
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin also noted that under the present
situation of the proliferation of parties, cabinet expansion is a
way to allow factions to express themselves as partners in the
government.
</P>
<P>
The bill is now being discussed by the Knesset Constitution
and Law Committee before returning to the Knesset plenum for
the second and third readings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
