<HEADLINE> U.S., Greek Defense Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen Tuesday held talks with his Greek counterpart, Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, on bilateral defense cooperation, Greece's role in
the reconstruction of the Balkans and the Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki, which also focused on the Cyprus problem, terrorism
and the the sale by the U.S. of specific weapons systems to
Greece, Cohen characterized Thessaloniki as "the port of hope" for
the future of the Balkans, the Thessaloniki-based Macedonian Press
Agency (MPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived Tuesday afternoon for an official two-day
visit, urged the intensification of efforts to tackle terrorism,
saying that terrorists in any part of the world must be brought to
justice.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for a peaceful solution to the Cyprus
problem, Cohen said that most likely this time it had already
come.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Tsohatzopoulos said that Greece's defense doctrine
was based on the fact that the country should have modern and
effective forces to act as a deterrent to a potential threat.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's visit has reportedly put the police force in the city
in a state of alert and strict security measures are in effect.
The Communist Party of Greece (KKE) has organized a demonstration
in the city to protest against Cohen's visit.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Cohen will meet in Athens with Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis and Foreign Minister George Papandreou.
</P>
</TEXT>
