<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Military Commission on DRC Ceasefire to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said Tuesday that the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the
United Nations will soon establish a Joint Military Commission
(JMC) to monitor the ceasefire agreement signed recently to end
the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba told the Zimbabwe News Agency in Algiers, Algeria, that
the OAU had already received the report on the ceasefire agreement
and was now working on modalities of sending peacekeepers and
appointing an independent chairperson of the Joint Military
Commission.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the war in the Congo will end soon. We can't continue
fighting because we do not have the resources to do so," he said,
adding that the money spent on military conflicts could be better
used for developmental purposes.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba expressed confidence that the peace agreement would
hold and that the rebels in the DRC would also sign it soon once
they put their house in order.
</P>
<P>
The rebels could not sign the agreement when leaders of Rwanda,
Uganda and Southern African Development Community, did so in
Lusaka because of a power struggle within the main Congolese Rally
for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
"No one was against the contents of the peace agreement
including the belligerents," Chiluba said, adding that the signing
of the agreement by several African leaders reflected that they
were happy with it and were committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
On reports that Rwanda and Uganda-backed rebels had intensified
the 11- month war only a few days after the signing of an
agreement, Chiluba said this could be a sign that the conflict was
coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
"It has to escalate before it goes down," he said without
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president said he would soon find ways to convince
the rebels to lay down their arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
