<HEADLINE> Progress Made Toward Peace in Horn of Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean President Isaias Afeworki
said here Tuesday afternoon that there has been progress made
toward peaceful resolution to the border conflict between his
country and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, the president said that
the Horn of Africa is moving toward peace and stability like other
parts of the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The Organization of African Unity (OAU) has pushed peace
process in some African countries like in Sierra Leone and in the
Democratic Republic of Congo," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that the conflict, which has lasted for
more than one year, will be resolved through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot say that much progress has been made. We are waiting
to see the final results of the summit," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the situation in his country is peaceful and
the economy is not much affected because it is growing quickly.
</P>
<P>
The border conflict between these two neighbors started in May
last year and resumed in February this year and later again in
June after a short repose. The OAU has provided a framework
agreement for the resolution of the conflict but it has not been
adequately implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
