<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Acts to Protect Hippopotami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawi is taking measures to
protect hippopotami community from being killed by poachers.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said the Malawi Ministry of Tourism,
Parks and Wildlife, in collaboration with the security
authorities, has contained a poaching threat against the
hippopotami community in the country's vast wetlands along the
Shire River, south of the commercial capital Blantyre.
</P>
<P>
Assistant parks and wildlife official, Joe Chinguwo, said
Tuesday that more than 500 hippos were recorded in 1994 in the
serenity and peaceful beauty of the marsh alongside the river.
</P>
<P>
But the figure declined drastically to between 200 and 300 now
due to skirmishes by poachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinguwo said the poachers, who camped in the village of
Yokoniya in the area, made big business selling the hippo meat,
hides and teeth.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has organized an education exercise for local
people, sensitizing the people along the marsh about the
importance of preserving the hippos for tourism purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The scouts of the tourism ministry, under police cover in
March, ambushed the village where they arrested four poachers and
uncovered various guns including AK 47s and muzzle loaders,
ammunition and knives used in killing and skinning the hippos.
</P>
<P>
The operation has made the area safe for hippos, noted
Chinguwo.
</P>
<P>
The tourism official said they would continue the education
program aimed at conserving areas where animals or plants are
under threats.
</P>
<P>
"If villagers understand the importance of conserving wildlife
they will not be involved in poaching," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Official Travels to Finland for Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior Egyptian official flew to
Helsinki, Finland on Tuesday for talks with Finnish officials on
regional issues and the ties between Egypt and the European Union
(EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon departure, Assistant Foreign
Minister Fathi el Shazli said he will discuss with Finnish
officials ways of seeking a more active role of the EU in helping
advance the Mideast peace process now that moderate Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak has come to power.
</P>
<P>
Finland is holding EU's rotating presidency for the second half
of this year. The EU desires to play a key role in helping
revitalize the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel and an active mediator in the Arab-Israeli peace talks,
keeps close contact with the EU on the issue.
</P>
<P>
El Shazli said he will also hold talks with Finnish officials
on the Egyptian-EU relations, which he described as "in an
important stage," referring to the finalization of the Egyptian-EU
partnership agreement.
</P>
<P>
After four years of negotiations, EU foreign ministers endorsed
last month the text of the agreement. But Egypt has yet to approve
the draft as what the country's chief negotiator Gamal Bayoumi
said there are around 15 clauses which remain to be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
The accord is aimed at providing for more open trade,
coordination in economic and financial areas, a political dialog
and joint efforts to combat money laundering and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, el Shazli is to prepare for a planned two-day
trip to the North European country by Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa on Thursday when el Shazli will be accompanying
Moussa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
