<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Sign Agreement on Steel Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
have signed an agreement limiting Russian shipments of steel to
the United States, avoiding imposition of punitive American
tariffs against Russian steel, U.S. officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed after marathon bargaining talks in Paris.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement had not been reached by July 13, the United
States was set to impose the penalty tariffs, which would have
resulted in an even steeper drop in demand for Russian steel in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The deal was achieved only at the last minute following a
number of concessions from the American side, the Associated Press
quoted Russian Trade Minister Mikhail Fradkov as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. steel industry claims that it has been hurt by a flood
of cheap imports into the country following the global currency
crisis, which sharply lowered demand for steel and other
commodities because of the steep recessions in many Asian nations
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The industry has filed a number of dumping cases seeking to get
the government to impose high tariffs to stem this tide of cheap
foreign steel into the country.
</P>
<P>
With political pressures rising, the Clinton Administration has
tried to show support for the U.S. steel industry. High tariffs
have been imposed in a case involving hot-rolled steel with Japan.
But Russia entered into negotiations to avoid having the tariffs,
which the industry favors because they are more effective at
halting imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Edges Up In June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The rate of inflation in Britain
rose slightly last month, although not enough to overshoot the
Government's target of 2.5 percent, according to official figures
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said the annual underlying
rate of inflation in June was 2.2 percent, up from 2.1 percent the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the effect pushing up the price index came from
alcoholic drink prices and housing costs, while downwards effects
came from falls in household goods prices and motoring costs.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed among economists in the City that there
is little inflationary pressure now in the UK, which could
persuade the Bank of England to cut interest rates once again.
</P>
</TEXT>
