<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute Lee Teng-hui's Separatist Remarks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUANZHOU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Scholars from the Chinese
mainland who are here for a symposium on cross-straits relations
met late tonight to refute the separatist remarks of Taiwan's Lee
Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
Lee said on July 9 in an interview with a German radio station
that cross-straits relations should be defined as "state-to-state
or at least special state-to-state relations" and this was echoed
later by other Taiwanese officials, who said that cross-straits
talks are "bilateral talks between two states."
</P>
<P>
Jiang Dianming, the vice-president of the Taiwan Studies
Society, said at the meeting that the separatist remarks are a
serious attack on the internationlly recognized principle that
there is only one China and they run contrary to the wish of the
Chinese people for the smooth development of the cross-straits
relations.
</P>
<P>
Lee's separatist remarks pose a great threat to the cross-
straits relations and the stability of cross-straits situation,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Lu Kaixuan, the president of the Tianjin Institute of
Agriculture and Forestry, said that Lee's remarks match the goals
of "Taiwan Independence" supporters and cater to the needs of anti-
China forces who hate to see a strong and unified China and want
to "make the Taiwan issue an international issue."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
