<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece to Facilitate Turkey's EU Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Greece have agreed to
lift objections to Turkey's bid to join the European Union (EU),
Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides told the Athens News
Agency (ANA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of Greek Foreign Ministry Yiannos Kranidiotis
said on Monday that it will be preferable if Turkey meets the
requirements set by EU leaders to be designated as an EU candidate.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Greece will allow Turkey to become an EU
candidate on two conditions: firstly, Cyprus' accession to the EU
would go ahead unhindered by a political solution to the Cyprus
issue being a prerequisite; secondly, a public statement of
solidarity from the EU on the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
While echoing Greece's position, the Cyprus foreign minister
said that the Greek government once again showed its dedication
toward Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island but
so far no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in 1990 and started
substantive accession negotiations with the EU in November
1998. It hopes to be admitted as an EU member by January 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
