<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM's Remarks on Cyprus Issue Draw Criticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's medieval views regarding
the solution of international issues, including that of Cyprus,
with the use of force do not conform with the international law,
Cyprus Government Spokesman Costas Serezis said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a statement made Monday by Turkish Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit that the Cyprus issue was solved in 1974, Serezis
noted that Ecevit himself had ordered Turkish troops to invade
Cyprus in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Serezis asked that if this was the case, then "why are the
U.N., the European Union, the G-8 (the seven most industrialized
nations plus Russia), the Non-Aligned Movement and the
Commonwealth" have been involved in efforts to solve the
longstanding Cyprus issue?
</P>
<P>
"The medieval theory that one country has the right, through
the use of force to solve international issues," Serezis said, is
"something which should concern Europe, if it wants Turkey to
join its ranks."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman also criticized Turkey for its
intention to change the island's demographic character.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish Cypriot press reports, there are now
less than 60,000 Turkish Cypriots in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has implanted more than 80,000 Turkish colonist
settlers in the northern area of the island, in addition to 35,000
Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
Before 1974 there were some 120,000 Turkish Cypriots in
Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
