<HEADLINE> Lebanon Renews Accusation of Israeli Soil Robbery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Tuesday renewed its
accusation that Israel is stealing the country's fertile soil and
taking it into northern Israel, the second charge since last
October.
</P>
<P>
The state-run National News Agency quoted sources in south
Lebanon as saying that the Israelis have been plundering Lebanese
soil since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Several Israeli trucks were seen to have transported soil from
Marjayoun district inside the Israeli occupied zone in south
Lebanon into northern Israel for the benefit of Israeli farmers.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in less than a year that Lebanon
charged Israel with stealing soil.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon had previously accused Israel of stealing south
Lebanon's water resources and using the volatile region to test
newly developed missiles.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
The agency also quoted Lebanese Foreign Ministry sources as
saying that Lebanon has asked the United Nations to help stop the
Israeli plunder.
</P>
<P>
It is a new Israeli aggression on Lebanon, which will force the
country to file a complaint to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan as it did last year, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli occupation forces and its ally South Lebanon Army
(SLA) out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
