<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Backs Annan's Decision on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Tuesday endorsed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
decision to start vote registration in East Timor on July 16, a
presidential statement said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time the 15 council members expressed concern over
the "serious" security situation in East Timor, particularly over
the recent incidents in some parts of the territory, which "has
highlighted the larger problem of militia impunity", the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued after the council heard a briefing from
the U.N. Secretariat on Annan's decision made last Saturday when
he put off the original registration date by 3 days because of
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Pro-integration and pro-independence militias in East Timor
have recently engaged in violent activities, according to U.N.
information.
</P>
<P>
The statement said council members welcomed the high-level
visit on Monday by members of the Indonesian cabinet to Dili,
capital of East Timor and their reaffirmation commitment to the
full implementation of the May 5 agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached after months of talks between Indonesia
and Portugal under the U.N. mediation, gives the U.N. mandate to
organize and conduct a "popular consultation" in East Timor to see
whether the majority of the local people want special autonomy
within Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a Portuguese colony until 1975, was occupied by
Indonesia the same year after a civil rift took place. In 1976
Indonesia annexed it and since then the U.N. has called it a
non-self-governing territory administered by Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The original ballot was set for August 8. Annan has postponed
it by two weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET),
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said on Monday that a
number of people were being investigated for their alleged
involvement in recent incidents and action will be taken to
prevent setting illegal roadblocks in the territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
