<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East African Treaty in Final Touches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Experts from east African
countries who have been meeting in north Tanzania's Arusha town
since June 29 have adopted a revised text for the establishment of
the East African Community.
</P>
<P>
The experts agreed on a 148-page revised draft treaty
containing 160 articles which cover various aspects of the new
regional cooperation organization to be formed on the basis of the
current East Africa Co- operation (EAC) comprising Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Alot Magaga, the public relations officer of EAC, said in
Arusha Tuesday that the revised draft has 33 chapters, covering
sectors of trade, customs, common market, infrastructure, human
resources and education.
</P>
<P>
Others are on free movement of personnel, health, environment,
culture, women, investment, industrial development, political
matters and the role of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The draft treaty envisages the eventual realization of a
political federation of east Africa, he said, adding "it will be
the responsibility of the heads of state to determine when such a
federation shall be established."
</P>
<P>
With the adoption of the revised text, the stage is now set for
the final lap to the signing of the treaty by heads of Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania scheduled for July 30 in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The revised text agreed by the high level treaty-making experts
will now be sent for consideration by an extraordinary meeting of
the EAC Permanent Tripartite Commission to be held in Arusha
between July 19 and 21.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Arusha, Magaga said the draft treaty
as reviewed by the commission "will be tabled at the meeting of
the attorneys general of the three member states during July 23
and 24, which will verify the legal content of the draft treaty."
</P>
<P>
Another meeting of the Permanent Tripartite Commission will be
convened during July 27 and 28 to clear the final text in
readiness for signature by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi,
Uganda's Yoweri Museveni and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The revised text, said the EAC official, has also incorporated
the views and amendment proposals from the public.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it has proposed the establishment of a customs
union and common market.
</P>
<P>
Within the customs union, internal tariffs and other charges on
imports will be eliminated, all non-tariffs barriers removed, and
application of a common external tariff effected.
</P>
<P>
The common market, however, said the draft, will be established
subject to protocols which will be concluded by the member states.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for World Aid to U.N. Mission in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Tuesday called on the international community to help the
United Nations Interim Administration in Kosovo (UNMIK) to meet
what he described "unprecedented challenges" in the post-war
reconstruction drive in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan said, ""The
Security Council has mandated the United Nations with an
unprecedented challenge in Kosovo. To meet this challenge and
fulfil the responsibilities entrusted to the Organization,
significant financial resources and personnel, including experts
in various fields, will be required immediately."
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo "remains tense," so Annan is
"particularly concerned about the continued harassment and lack of
security of minority groups in Kosovo," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is locked in tensions due to lack of law, and the
international peacekeepers, known as KFOR, and UNMIK are not fully
deployed.
</P>
<P>
"The full deployment of KFOR and UNMIK personnel will
undoubtedly contribute to the easing of these tensions," Annan
said. "In order to create a climate of law and order, UNMIK must
deploy international police throughout Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Annan also appealed for the quick deployment of civilian police
to Kosovo as well as money to pay civil servants before public
services collapsed entirely.
</P>
<P>
"Their early arrival is essential if we are to stem the
tendency toward lawlessness which is taking hold in some areas,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
So far about 1,900 police have been pledged by 41 countries
several hundred more are needed for border units and special task
forces, a senior U.N. official told a press conference. He said he
had received only 968 names of officers who would actually go to
the Yugoslav province beginning July 17.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the work of UNMIK will be conducted in five
integrated phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will focus on the establishment and
consolidation of UNMIK's authority and the creation of interim
UNMIK-managed administrative structures.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will be directed towards the administration of
social services and utilities, and the consolidation of the rule
of law, he said.
</P>
<P>
The third phase, after progress being made in the second one,
will be the finalization of preparation for and the conduct of
elections to what may be termed the Kosovo Transitional Authority,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth phase is the period in which UNMIK will oversee and,
as necessary, assist elected Kosovo representatives in their
efforts to organize and establish provisional institutions for
democratic and autonomous self-government, he said.
</P>
<P>
A concluding fifth phase will depend on a final settlement and
the dispositions made therein, he said.
</P>
<P>
"During the interim period, UNMIK will endeavour to promote, in
cooperation with KFOR, an atmosphere of security and safety that
will enable all refugees and internally displaced persons,
regardless of their ethnicity, to return freely to their homes and
live there in conditions in which the highest standards of human
rights and fundamental freedoms are respected," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
