<HEADLINE> Britain, Argentina Hold Talks On Falkland Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations between Britain and
Argentina on how to resume air links between the disputed Falkland
Islands and the Argentine mainland are expected to reach agreement
on Wednesday, British Foreign Office said.
</P>
<P>
The talks, in their third round in London now, are due to
continue on Wednesday morning and a statement is expected to be
issued around noon, a spokeswoman in the Foreign office told
Xinhua on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They are being attended by British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
and his Argentine counterpart Guido di Tella and councillors from
the Falklands.
</P>
<P>
"They had made good progress today," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, a war broke out between Britain and Argentina over the
sovereignty of the Falkland Island, which lies off the Argentine
coast. Argentina has claimed sovereignty of that island, which was
called "Las Malvinas" by Argentine, since 1833.  
</P>
</TEXT>
