<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Main Bourses Close in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON July 13 (Xinhua) - Main European stock markets suffered
sizable losses at the close Tuesday, as the disappointing data at
home and the sharp fall in Argentine stock market hurt investors'
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 in London closed down 99.9 points, or 1.53
percent, at 6445.6, as early losses on Wall Street mounted and
banking stocks fell on benign UK inflation data.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outgunned gainers by more than seven-to-one in London
as bank and telecom shares drifted off recent highs.
</P>
<P>
British banks were hit by June inflation figures that came in
exactly in line with expectations of an annual increase of 2.2
percent, raising speculation that the current round of interest
rate cuts is at an end.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt, lost 78.20 points to end at
5573.82, a fall of 1.38 percent, as investors bailed out on the
back of disappointing retail sales figures and lower prospects for
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Among individual stocks HypoVereinsbank led the decline among
banks, falling 3.8 percent. Deutsche Bank was the most traded
stock and also fell 3 percent, while Dresdner Bank was down 3.33
percent.
</P>
<P>
Car maker BMW, was the leading faller, down 3.97 percent amid
profit-taking after rising to its highest price since February on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
French shares fell lower on the day as weaker than expected
German economic data and sharp losses in Argentina overnight
prompted profit-taking. The CAC 40 fell 67.63 points, or 1.45
percent, to end at 4594.65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
