<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Withdraws From U.S. Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Representative John
Kasich from Ohio has decided to drop out of the race for the
Republican presidential nomination, Republican officials said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kasich decided to withdraw to support the Republican
presidential front-runner, Texas Governor George W. Bush, said the
officials. He is expected to make a formal announcement of
withdrawal on Wednesday afternoon in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old Kasich, chairman of the House of
Representatives Budget Committee, is also expected to announce
that he will not seek re-election to a tenth two-year term in
Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another Republican presidential hopeful, New
Hampshire Senator Bob Smith, announced Tuesday that he abandoned
the Republican party to join the U.S. Taxpayers Party nomination
for the White House as a third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
Kasich and Smith made their decisions of withdrawal after Bush
solidified his claim as front-runner in the Republican nomination
race with record fund-raising of more than 36 million dollars for
the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Departure of Kasich and Smith from the Republican
presidential race will reduce the number of contenders for the
party's 2000 nomination to 10.
</P>
<P>
Republican officials said they expect other contenders to drop
out after the August 14 straw poll in Iowa. Traditionally, the
party's eventual nominee for presidential election comes from the
top three in the poll.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
