<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hill Drives On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- British driver Damon Hill has
announced he will carry on in Formula One until the end of the
1999 season.
</P>
<P>
The announcement ends nearly a month of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
Hill confirmed he was retiring at the end of the season, then
hinted that he would go immediately after a disastrous French
Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
He was persuaded to change his mind after meeting with team
owner Eddie Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The driver refused to discuss his future during a successful
weekend at Silverstone, which saw him finish fifth in the race.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old former world champion said on Wednesday: "I am
looking forward to helping the Jordan team achieve their highest-
ever Constructors' Championship position."
</P>
<P>
The team are currently third in the race for this title.
</P>
<P>
Team chief executive Jordan added: "We are all extremely
pleased with Damon's decision.
</P>
<P>
"His contribution to this massive team effort is invaluable and
we are all eagerly anticipating the last eight races."
</P>
<P>
Both Hill and Jordan are on holiday with their families this
week while the team tests at Monza with Shinji Nakano and Heinz-
Harald Frentzen.
</P>
<P>
Hill's decision came as no real surprise after Jordan himself
hinted on Monday that the driver was likely to carry on.
</P>
<P>
Last year he performed much better in the second half of the
season - bringing Jordan their first GP win in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Talk of premature retirement this season came when he was at a
low ebb in France, his fifth failure to finish in seven races.
</P>
<P>
The Briton had also been eclipsed by team-mate Heinz-Harald
Frentzen, who won the French race.
</P>
<P>
There are also few drivers available of the caliber required to
slot in to Hill's place, and one fewer after Ferrari's appointment
of Mika Salo to stand in for the injured Michael Schumacher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
