<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak New Trade Policy to Diversify, Expand Export Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
Wednesday announced its annual trade policy for new fiscal year
(July 1-June 30) which sets export target at nine billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new trade policy announced here by Finance Minister Ishaq
Dar envisages various concessions and tax incentives and relief to
expand and diversify export base, propelling foreign exchange
earnings and trimming trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Dar spelled out various measures and steps in the trade policy
to remove the stumbling blocks which hamper export expansion, and
to facilitate exporters to concentrate on value-addition.
</P>
<P>
The policy measures will eliminate anti-export biases retarding
the export growth and put the economy on a sound track, he said.
</P>
<P>
The trade policy sets the annual target of exports at nine
billion dollars and that of imports at 9.8 billion dollars,
bringing down the trade deficit to 800 million dollars against
1.57 billion dollars during 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed the need of renewed role of the private
sector which would gear up investments, exports and growth process
in an effective fashion.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet earlier approved the trade policy after detailed
discussion on various aspects of imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif also
discussed different measures for creating more jobs and boosting
exports.
</P>
<P>
Dar said that in order to promote exports of engineering,
contracting and consulting services, there will be only one
percent income tax on foreign exchange earnings of this sector.
</P>
<P>
The export of rice, he said, is now subjected to one percent
income tax. This ratio is being curtailed to half a percent to
promote the rice export, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dar also said that the income tax imposed on the exports of
fish and other edible items is being reduced to 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's exports in fiscal 1998-99 stood at only 7.72 billion
dollars as against the target of 10 billion dollars. Exports in
1997-98 reached 8.63 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total bill of imports in 1998-99 was 9.28
billion dollars, registering a trade deficit of 1.56 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government had vowed to achieve zero-rate trade
deficit during the last fiscal year when it announced its trade
policy for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
Despite efforts to contain the deficit, it has been on the rise
gradually due to stagnation in exports and rise in import bill
following the reduction of import duties from 45 to 35 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
