<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Rise Slightly in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. retail sales rose just 0.1
percent in June to a seasonally adjusted 243.3 billion dollars,
the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The June increase followed a big 1.2 percent gain in retail
sales in May. The last month's small advance reflected a sharp
drop in automotive sales.
</P>
<P>
However, retail sales, which represent one third of the
nation's economic output, have climbed or held steady for 11
months running and were 8 percent higher than in June of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said consumers' strong appetite for shopping is being
fueled by the country's economic boom. Consumer confidence is high
as both unemployment and inflation remain low, and the stock
market continues to post record gains.
</P>
<P>
In June, despite the overall increase in retail sales,
automotive sales fell a sharp 1 percent while sales at gasoline
stations also went down 0.4 percent. But without the often
volatile autos category, retail sales would have increased 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of durable goods fell 0.4 percent in June following a
strong 2.3 percent increase in May.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, also were up
in June, rising 0.4 percent, following a 0.5 percent increase in
May.
</P>
<P>
Last month, sales at apparel and accessory shops rose 0.2
percent and sales at department and general merchandise stores
increased 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last week the nation's biggest retailers reported surprisingly
strong sales in June and warm weather took people buying
everything from bathing suits to air conditioners. Discount
chains, such as Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart, were the biggest
winners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
