<HEADLINE> Greek, Albanian, Macedonian Foreign Ministers Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of Greece,
Albania and Macedonia Wednesday agreed on the establishment of
joint committees for the development, democratization and
reconstruction of the Balkans within the framework of the
stability pact.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached while the three ministers were
meeting at the Agios Achillios islet, in the northern Greek region
of Prespes, within the framework of a relevant initiative by
Athens, the Thessaloniki-based Macedonia Press Agency (MPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
During the first such tripartite meeting, Greek Foreign
Minister George Papandreou and his Albanian and Macedonian
counterparts, Paskal Milo and Aleksander Dimitrov, discussed
multilateral cooperation in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Describing the tripartite meeting as "historical," Papandreou
said that those meetings would be in the future upgraded and would
be held at prime ministers' level and at ministerial level in
order to broaden the cooperation among the three countries within
the framework of the stability pact that would be implemented in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The Greek side reportedly wants these tripartite meetings to
take place every six months.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou also said that Greece regarded as necessary for
Albania and Macedonia to receive assistance as they were mostly
hit by the crisis in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
