<HEADLINE> Winnipeg Deadly Lab leak Causes Growing Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian media voiced growing
concern on Wednesday about the deadly lab leak in the city of
Winnipeg, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
Many provincial officials demand to know why they were not told
in time after a Level 4 lab dumped waste water into city sewers,
according to the media.
</P>
<P>
The lab is reported to be one of just a dozen in the world
capable of handling the deadliest of viruses such as Ebola, Lassa
and Marbug.
</P>
<P>
Although Manitoba's Environment Minister Linda McIntosh assured
Tuesday that "no viral containments will be entering the water
system," and the federal government was asked to review the safety
facility at the lab, the media said.
</P>
<P>
So far there has been no report of any illness caused from the
deadly discharge.
</P>
<P>
The accidental leak occurred on June 23 but only came to light
in news reports three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
The waste water was sent to a lab sewer tank but then
discharged by mistake into a large blending tank that mixes waste
from other labs in the facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
