<HEADLINE> IATA Urges NATO to Remove No-fly Zones Around Kosovo Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Air Transport
Association (IATA) urged NATO here Tuesday to immediately lift
flight ban over the Kosovo region.
</P>
<P>
"At least 30 percent of the increased air traffic control
delays in the last three months have been caused by diverting
civilian flights around the Kosovo region into Italy, France and
Eastern Europe," the IATA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
After the end of NATO's 11-week air strikes against Yugoslavia
in June, no-fly zones set up over Croatia, Serbia, Macedonia,
Albania, southern Hungary, Bosnia and the Adriatic Sea during the
Kosovo conflict were still in operation, according to the IATA.
</P>
<P>
"Immediate action must be taken to help this summer's
bottlenecks," the Geneva-based IATA said. "As the Kosovo conflict
is over, NATO and all relevant states must immediately return the
region's airspace to normal use." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
