<HEADLINE> India Asks Pakistan to Restart Lahore Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- India's caretaker Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee Wednesday asked Pakistan to restart Lahore
peace process, which began last February when he and Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif signed the Lahore Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The Lahore Declaration was a "firm commitment between India and
Pakistan to resolve all issues bilaterally and what happened in
Kargil (of Kashmir) was totally against this commitment," Vajpayee
said at a public rally in Kulu, a northern city.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Vajpayee said, Pakistan should make a fresh
beginning to carry forward the Lahore peace process which the
Indian leader said had been marred by incursions in Kargil.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India (PTI), India would not
wait indefinitely for the intruders to withdraw, Vajpayee told the
rally, adding that they would be thrown out if they refuse to
vacate Indian territory.
</P>
<P>
Asserting that the conflict in Kashmir was not completely over,
Vajpayee said his country would not stop the retreating intruders
and expected them to leave immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan stabbed us in the back and considered the present
uncertain political situation (in India as) an opportune time to
push in intruders, but a tide of nationalism swept India which
united us like a rock," PTI quoted Vajpayee as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee assured the army that it would be equipped with the
latest weapons and equipment that would be either imported or
manufactured domestically.
</P>
<P>
He refused to give any comments when asked about Pakistan's
statement that no date had been fixed for complete withdrawal of
"Mujaheedins" from all sectors in Kargil area.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee indicated that, during his talks with Sharif in
Lahore, the issue of so-called line of control (LoC)in Kashmir had
not been raised.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan should have raised the LoC issue during the Lahore
talks if it had any reservations about it, Vajpayee said, adding
there was no such mention at that time.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee reiterated that the Indian army was determined to
throw out the last infiltrator from Indian side.
</P>
<P>
In New Delhi, Defense Minister George Fernandes echoed what
Vajpayee said Wednesday, warning Pakistan of grave consequences if
it backtracked from its commitment to withdraw forces from Kargil.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Pakistan's reported statement that the July 16
deadline for withdrawal was a "big lie", Fernandes said "Pakistan
speaks with one voice for its people and with another voice for
India." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
