<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Tariff Reductions on Track: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of 12 southern
African trade ministers opened in Botswanan capital Gaborone
Wednesday with officials optimistic about implementation of the
phased reduction of tariffs between their countries in the year
2000, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the 14 member states of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC), only the Democratic Republic of Congo and
Seychelles were not represented.
</P>
<P>
The officials agreed that there could be compromise on the
original protocol under which the tariffs will be reduced. But
they remain confident that it will finally be ratified by the time
of a SADC heads of state summit in August.
</P>
<P>
This will clear the way for tariffs on at least 60 percent of
goods traded between member states to be abolished by January 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
Malawi and South Africa are in line to be at least two states
that will ratify. They would make up the seven needed to
implement the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Members of the South African delegation said Wednesday that
they were unhappy with the handling of negotiations so far by
trade sector coordinating country Tanzania and would propose
amendments.
</P>
<P>
"Things are moving too slowly, communications between ourselves
and some of the other member states are difficult," they said. "We
want to reshuffle the responsibilities.... but things will still
happen by the end of the year."
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki said at the World Economic
Forum's Southern Economic Summit in Durban last week that South
Africa would ratify the protocol to allow for its implementation
in January, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Botswana Commerce Minister George Kgoroba
said that the implementation of the trade protocol is the greatest
challenge facing the SADC.
</P>
<P>
"It will tell potential investors that the SADC is ready for
them," SAPA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is the way to achieve full regional integration in the
shortest possible time," the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
SADC Deputy Executive Secretary Prega Ramsamy said the
implementation would show how ready the SADC is to become a
serious player in the international economic arena.
</P>
<P>
"We must put our house in order," he said. "Members must be
flexible in today's negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Chungu Mwila of the SADC secretariat said negotiations had come
a long way. He expected agreement, but also warned of final
compromise.
</P>
<P>
"Wednesday will be decisive," he said. "The ministers are under
pressure to deliver."
</P>
<P>
"This is the real world. The crunch of the matter is that some
of the countries were trying to hang on to some tariffs even in
non-sensitive categories," the SADC official said. "Now they are
more accommodating."
</P>
<P>
Negotiations had snagged previously on rules of origin and the
textile and motor assembly industries. Some members had
classified goods they were not trading in as from 'essential'
industries that had to be protected.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Botswana, Tanzania, Zimbabwe, Namibia and
Mauritius have already ratified the protocol, which seeks to
establish a tariff-free zone within eight years of its signing in
Maseru, capital of Lesotho, in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the original signatories have to ratify the
document before the SADC secretariat can start the process of
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The SADC in August 1996 had only 12 members. All but Angola
signed, so two-thirds of 11 is taken as seven.
</P>
<P>
"Angola did not sign then, (the Democratic) Congo and
Seychelles were not members, but the rule is that they will have
to go along with the rest," secretariat spokesperson Kito Segwai
said.
</P>
<P>
Three phases of tariff reduction are planned. Items in group A
which account for 60 percent of traded goods, will kick in with a
zero tariff rating on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on group B items will be liberalized gradually over the
five remaining years of the eight year period.
</P>
<P>
Group C is for 'sensitive' items.
</P>
<P>
Mwila said that broadly defined, the A group was everything
except textiles, clothing, assembled motor vehicles, leather goods
and some agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
He foresaw last minute special arrangements for sugar and beef
and the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
The 14 member states of the SADC are: Angola, Botswana,
Democratic Congo, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia,
Seychelles, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
