<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hails Egyptian-Sudanese Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
on Wednesday spoke highly of a recent meeting between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and his Sudanese counterpart Omar
al-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting is a key step on the way to progress of the
bilateral ties," Moussa told Egypt's Middle East News Agency on
the sidelines of the 35th summit of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) in the Algerian capital of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the two countries "would maintain good
cooperation in the near future."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister stressed Egypt's keenness on
Sudan's unity and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's rebel groups have been fighting a 16-year-old war for
greater autonomy in southern states from the Khartoum Islamic
government.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been in close contacts with Sudan's opposition
groups, including the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, in an
effort to advise them to refrain from splitting the south from the
north. Cairo fears that a dismembered Sudan will endanger the
Nile, its major water source.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak met on Monday with al-Bashir on the sidelines of the
OAU summit in Algiers, a move rare in the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Mubarak said the bilateral relations "are
continually improving."
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-Khartoum ties soured in 1995 after Egypt accused
Sudan of masterminding an assassination attempt on Mubarak in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also blamed Sudan for sheltering Islamic militants who
have been waging an insurgency since 1992 in an attempt to
topple the secular Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
The ties have been improving steadily in the recent two years
after the two sides repeatedly expressed readiness to end tensions
and exchanged visits by senior officials. It has been reported
that the two sides are considering a visit to Egypt by the
Sudanese president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
