<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The Colombian leftwing guerrillas were accused of recruiting
thousands of children and teenagers into their ranks to fight
government forces. Among the 287 guerrrillas killed in a battle
with government forces last week, 70 were children of from nine to
15 years old.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The ministers of finance of the Group of Seven (G-7) most
industrialized nations and the president of World Bank met on
Tuesday in Brussels to discuss Kosovo reconstruction and economic
aid for its neighboring countries. The European Commission
estimated that from 25 billion to 30 billion euros (25.3 billion
to 30.4 billion U.S. dollars) are needed to help the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
-- London's Sotheby's auction shop will put on sale archives on
35 years of the personal life of Charles Dickens. The archives
showed that the writer, who so successfully depicted the misery of
Victorian Britain, was himself a dubious businessman and a
terrible quibbler. 
</P>
