<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Evaluate Environmental Damage In Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will send a team
of experts to Yugoslavia next week to evaluate environmental
damage caused by NATO's 11-week military attacks against the
country, U.N. officials announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen of experts will begin their study in Belgrade on
July 19 and then split up to work in the Kosovo capital of
Pristina and in Pancevo, an industrial town where an oil refinery
and petrochemical plant were hit by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
"The task force on the Balkans is leaving at the weekend and
will start work Monday in Belgrade," a U.N. Environment Program (
UNEP) spokeswoman told a news briefing in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Pekka Haavisto, a former Finnish environment minister who will
head the mission, said the trip would go ahead despite a lack of
detailed information from NATO about its bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The military information is not on the table," Haavisto said.
"But we have all the background information available which is a
good basis for our work."
</P>
<P>
He said that the experts "are trying to get information from
all sources and have established good contacts with KFOR (
peacekeeping) troops. From their side we have the first reports
from villages, which is very useful."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team will try to assess the possible impact on water
resources and the food chain and check whether depleted uranium
was released into the air and soil.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Commission on Human Settlement is helping to organize
the mission, which will also look into damage to housing. The U.N.
refugee agency, the leading humanitarian agency in Kosovo, has
estimated 65 percent of the province's homes were damaged or
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Serb authorities say NATO's air strikes targeted fuel
refineries, fertilizer plants, petrochemical units and storage
tanks and has caused an environmental nightmare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
