<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges India to Hand over 3 Officers' Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday urged India to
hand over three Pakistani military officers' bodies and not to
"play games" with them.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office spokesman Rafiq Altaf told journalists here that
Pakistan has since Tuesday contacted the Indian Foreign Ministry
and the International Committee of Red Cross in a bid to get those
bodies but failed so far.
</P>
<P>
He said India informed Pakistan Tuesday that three Pakistani
military officers' bodies were available and asked Pakistan to
accept them.
</P>
<P>
But the bodies, which have been taken to New Delhi "for some
propaganda purpose", are so far unavailable to related Pakistani
officials. "We even don't know where they are," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
India wanted a formal note on identification of the dead from
Pakistan for the return of the bodies, but Pakistan insisted that
the bodies should be handed over before any identification, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
According to the names given by the Indian side, the three dead
are separately Captain Iftikhar, Major Iqbal and Captain Karnal
Shakh.
</P>
<P>
They are among those missing in Indian ambushes or Indian
attacks on the Line of Control during the two-month fighting in
Kashmir, according to Altaf.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indians are playing games on the bodies and trying
to misuse them to "prove what they want to prove", which is "a
very sad affair".
</P>
<P>
Touching upon another issue, the spokesman said the Line of
Control is the cease-fire line mapped out according to the Simla
Agreement in 1972, and "it is just a line of control and no more
than that".
</P>
<P>
No one can infuse new meaning to the Line of Control, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kashmir dispute is not a border dispute, but is an
issue of the fate of the Kashmiri people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
