<HEADLINE> India to Get 2 Billion U.S. Dollars From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- India is all set to get at least
two billion U.S. dollars of loans from the World Bank during the
current financial year for various social development projects
following the easing of economic sanctions since May last year.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Indian government signed two agreements with
the World Bank involving 135 million dollars of loan for the
second integrated watershed development project covering five
northern states and a 105 million U.S. dollars loan for the second
phase of urban development project in the southern state of Tamil
Nadu.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi has already signed agreements with international
financial institutions for over 600 million U.S. dollars in the
past week.
</P>
<P>
According to Additional Secretary in charge of fund-bank V.
Govindarajan, the next few months would see more projects worth
over one billion U.S. dollars for water, health and education
programs.
</P>
<P>
Also last week, India inked two loan agreements worth 386
million U.S. dollars with the World Bank to finance women and
child development in five states and another for primary education
in Rajasthan. 
</P>
