<HEADLINE> Intruders to Be Treated as "Hostile" After July 16: India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- India sternly warned Pakistan
Wednesday that any intruder found in the Kargil sector of Kashmir
after July 16 deadline for withdrawal would be treated as
"hostile" towards India.
</P>
<P>
"We expect Pakistan to keep its commitment on the time frame
under which the withdrawal must take place," a spokesman of the
External Affairs Ministry said at the regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the deadline, he added, "enemy personnel seen on our
side of the so-called line of control (LoC) would be treated as
hostile and dealt with accordingly."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made these remarks in response to a question on a
report quoting the Pakistani Foreign Office that no deadline of
July 16 had been agreed to for pull-out of the intruders during
the meeting of the Directors General of Military Operations of the
two countries last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Kargil
that Indian troops moved very close to the LoC in Batalik and
Drass sectors.  
</P>
