<HEADLINE> Expedition to Search Bodies of Hong Kong Climbers Missing 11 Months Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 16 Chinese climbers,
including several from Hong Kong and Taiwan Province, on Wednesday
launched an expedition to recover the bodies of three Hong Kong
climbers died in snowstorm 11 months ago at Mt. Bogda.
</P>
<P>
Chan King-chuen, Lam Chi-wai and Yeung Chi-ho went missing at 5,
080 meters on August 15, 1998 when they attempted to scale the 5,
445-meter peak in the Xinjiang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Ziyun, head of the searching expedition, said on Wednesday
that they hope to find bodies or relic of the trio which may be
exposed with the melting of snow and ice in the summer.
</P>
<P>
The expedition said the missing climbers may either dropped to
their death at 5,080 or died in sleeping as heavy snowstorm hit
them unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the Ngok Fung Rock Climbing Society, of which the
missing trio were members, the Xinjiang Mountaineering Association
and the Chinese Army had put up a joint rescuing operation, which
was greatly hampered by heavy snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
The rescuers only found an empty tent with equipment buried in
snow at 4,700 meters. They stopped the operation on August 30,
fearing the trio had died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
