<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Court Rejects Appeal By Corrupt Official To Reverse Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Higher People's Court of south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region today announced the
result of its second-instance trial of Li Chenglong, former deputy
mayor of Guigang City, and upheld a lower court ruling of death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
He was also stripped of all political rights, fined 100,000
yuan worth of personal property, and had to return all the money
and gifts he received as bribes.
</P>
<P>
The court investigation found that, from 1991 to 1996 when Li
was serving as Party Secretary of Yulin City, he accepted bribes
from 21 individuals and organizations that were worth 3.74 million
yuan, along with 25,000 U.S. dollars and 10,000 HK dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
When he was arrested in December 1996, his personal assets were
found to be worth more than 15.27 million yuan and 25,000 U.S.
dollars in cash, in addition to various amounts of HK dollars,
Australian dollars and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The intermediate people's court in the city of Yulin gave him
the death penalty on January 27, 1999 and Li appealed to the
higher people's court, which investigated further before upholding
the original finding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
