<HEADLINE> Cohen Stresses Greece's Role in Balkan Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen stressed on Wednesday Greece's leading role in the
reconstruction of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the U.S. embassy in Athens,
Cohen, who arrived in Greece on Tuesday for an official two-day
visit, said that Greece had a very significant role in the Balkan
reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the European Union leaders decided to base its
agency for the reconstruction of the Balkans in the northern Greek
city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
To participate in the reconstruction effort, the U.S.
government also intended to create a trade office in the northern
Greek city.
</P>
<P>
As for Greek's relations with Turkey, Cohen described the talks
at high-ranking Foreign Ministry level that were to begin soon as
"very important".
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was now encouraging Greece and Turkey to find a
peaceful solution to their disputes, but the U.S. did not seek to
become in any way an arbitrator or in any way to pressure either
government, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of terrorism, Cohen said that the U.S. condemned
all forms of terrorism. The U.S. would look positively on an
exchange of information and cooperation with Greece in combating
terrorism, he added.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, Cohen met with Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis, Foreign Minister George Papandreou and the main
opposition New Democracy leader Costas Karamanlis to discuss Greek-
Turkish relations, terrorism, the Cyprus problem and matters of
bilateral interest. 
</P>
