<HEADLINE> Iran to Investigate Attack on Student Dormitory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's top security body on
Wednesday promised to investigate into the unauthorized police
attack on the Tehran University dormitory compound, which
triggered a six-day unrest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC)
Hassan Rowhani told a massive rally in Tehran University that the
SNSC, headed by President Mohammad Khatami, would investigate the
recent incidents and inform the public of the outcome, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Rowhani, also vice Majlis (parliament) speaker, also assured
that the government has full control over the situation.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of university students clashed with anti-riot police
in recent days in the wake of the police assault on the Tehran
University dormitory last Thursday night following a student rally
protesting the newly-approved press law and the closure of the
leading moderate daily Salam (Hello).
</P>
<P>
Millions of people Wednesday gathered in Tehran University and
streets nearby, condemning the recent police attack on student
hostels and the consequent unrest.
</P>
<P>
In a seven-point resolution, the demonstrators called on the
authorities to identify and punish those involved in the attack
and bring an end to the unrest during the past six days, the worst
since the 1979 Islamic revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
