<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1430 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A U.N. technical team to remove toxic chemical
substances left behind in the Baghdad laboratory of the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq arrived in Baghdad
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, sent by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and
led by South Africa's chemical production technologist Dirk van
Niekerk, is to meet Annan's special representative in Baghdad
Prakash Shah and three senior diplomats from the Chinese, Russian
and French embassies in Baghdad before it will carry out its
mission. The U.N. team comprises four chemical experts from the
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons in the Hague
and an independent biological weapons expert. (Iraq-UN Team)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States reiterated on Tuesday its "
three-no" policy and the "one China" position which it sees as in
conformity with America's national interests.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin, Spokesman for the State Department, told a regular
news briefing that "We do not support Taiwan independence. We do
not support Taiwanese membership in organizations where statehood
is required. We do not support a two-China policy or a one-China,
one-Taiwan policy." The "three-no" policy on Taiwan was brought to
life by President Bill Clinton on June 30 last year in Shanghai
when he paid a state visit to China. (US-Taiwan-Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada has agreed to drop its plan to sell its only
nuclear fusion reactor and related technology to Iran, which the
United States takes as anti-American.
</P>
<P>
The "National Post" newspaper of Canada said Wednesday that
Washington had contacted the Canadian Foreign Ministry and
received "strong assurances that Canada will block the proposed
sale." The U.S. is concerned that Iran has become expert at
procuring industrial production technologies in order to build
weapons of mass destruction, according to the newspaper. The U.S.
may agree that Canada sells the fusion technology to responsible
nations, the newspaper indicated. (Canada-Iran-Reactor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen
stressed on Wednesday Greece's leading role in the reconstruction
of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the U.S. embassy in Athens,
Cohen, who arrived in Greece on Tuesday for an official two-day
visit, said that Greece had a very significant role in the Balkan
reconstruction effort. Last month, the European Union leaders
decided to base its agency for the reconstruction of the Balkans
in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki. To participate in the
reconstruction effort, the U.S. government also intended to create
a trade office in the northern Greek city.(Greece-US-Balkan
Reconstruction) 
</P>
