<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Genocide Suspect's Extradition Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The extradition case
concerning Bernard Ntuyahaga, a former Rwandan army officer wanted
by both Rwanda and Belgium for his role in the 1994 Rwanda
genocide, is adjourned to July 28.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was brought to the Kisutu Resident Magistrate's Court
in Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam Wednesday, but his counsel
Jwain Mwaikusa said that a Belgian lawyer to defend the accused
has not arrived yet.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian lawyer, Luc de Temmerman, has mailed his curriculum
vitae, professional certificates and other needed documents to
Tanzania's Chief Justice applying to jointly defend Ntuyahaga, but
the Chief Justice has not made any response so far, Mwaikusa told
the court.
</P>
<P>
Even when the Chief Justice endorses the application, time is
still needed to hear the case as Temmerman will travel to Spain
until July 22, Mwaikusa said.
</P>
<P>
"I pray for another mention date in two weeks time," he said.
The Principal Resident Magistrate Projestus Rugazia, who presided
over the case, agreed to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Major Ntuyahaga, the former head of Logistics at Kigali
military camp in Rwanda, allegedly murdered former Rwandan Prime
Minister Agathe Uwiningiyimana and 10 Belgium U.N. peace-keepers
escorting her in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old man fell into the hand of the Tanzanian
government in March this year after the International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR), based in Arusha in north Tanzania,
dropped charges of genocide and crimes against humanity against
him and released him in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was re-arrested by the Tanzanian police and wanted by
both Rwanda and Belgium for extradition and trial.
</P>
<P>
At present, Ntuyahaga is defended by Tanzanian lawyer,
Mwaikusa, a teacher at the Law Department of the University of Dar
es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
However, the accused alleged that he has language problems and
needs Temmerman, who has been his lawyer since 1995, to work
together with Mwaikusa.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga's case has been adjourned several times since it was
heard by the Kisutu court on May 12 this year.
</P>
<P>
Mwaikusa later told Xinhua that when the case comes two weeks
from now, he believes the Chief Justice will have decided to say
yes or no to the Belgian lawyer's application.
</P>
<P>
"If he says no, I'll immediately ask for a hearing date so that
we proceed," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If he says yes... hopefully I will be able to know the
decision before that date (July 28) then I'll communicate with
this man there to tell him ' now you have been allowed. So please
make arrangements to come down here'... " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Publishes Policy Initiatives on Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) Thursday published a package of policy initiatives to
reform the local banking market and to improve safety and
soundness of the local banking sector.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives are largely drawn from the recommendations
contained in the Banking Sector Consultancy Study published in
January this year, said David Carse, deputy chief executive of
HKMA, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Two of the more prominent features of this reform package
concern the deregulation of the remaining interest rate rules and
enhancing depositor protection in Hong Kong, Carse said.
</P>
<P>
Having carefully considered the views of the banking industry
and other non-bank organizations, such as the Consumer Council,
the HKMA plans to deregulate the remaining interest rate rules
within a shorter time scale than that recommended by the
consultants, while ensuring that this takes place in a relatively
stable economic and financial environment.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of deregulation, scheduled to take place on
July 1, 2000, will see the restrictions on the remaining
regulated time deposits lifted.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate rules on current and saving accounts will be
deregulated together in the second phase, which would take place
12 months after the first phase.
</P>
<P>
On depositor protection, the HKMA considers it appropriate to
carry out a full study in the first half of 2000 into the
feasibility and desirability of a deposit insurance scheme or
other forms of depositor protection in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Regarding other measures to strengthen the safety and soundness
of the banking system, the HKMA clarified its role as the lender
of last resort in a policy statement announced last month.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA will also continue its work on improving the
disclosure framework for all authorized institutions in Hong Kong
and is taking steps to develop a more formalized risk-based
approach to banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
On the banking sector reform side, the HKMA will undertake a
thorough review next year of ways to convert the current three-
tier system of authorization into a two-tier system.
</P>
<P>
It will also take immediate measures to relax the one branch
policy currently applicable to most foreign banks and to allow
access by restricted license banks to the Real Time Gross
Settlement system.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the initiatives arising from the recommendations
of the consultants, this package of policy initiatives contains
measures which the HKMA wishes to pursue in order to further
enhance safety and soundness of the banking system as a whole.
</P>
<P>
These additional initiatives include a feasibility study on
establishing a credit register to provide relevant information to
lending institutions on corporate enterprises' overall
indebtedness, and measures to promote higher standards of
corporate governance among authorized institutions through
strengthening the role of the board of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Government Calls for NLD's Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government Wednesday
called for cooperation from the National League for Democracy
(NLD), an opposition political party in the country, by retracting
its 10-member "Committee Representing the People's Parliament
(CRPP) Elected in the 1990 General Election" formed last year.
</P>
<P>
"The government wishes the NLD to act in a more pragmatic and
sensible way so that a positive and a meaningful interaction can
be resumed without any interruption again," said a government
statement released here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"The government believes that the process could be managed with
the NLD's retraction of the committee," the official Information
Sheet stated.
</P>
<P>
The government views with great concern over the committee's
saying that it will act as an interim parliament, it said, adding
that the NLD's move would not lead to a stable democracy, but to
institutional confusion, social chaos and genuine political
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the NLD to take serious consideration on
the retraction call and contribute in a responsible and
constructive manner to achieving their common goals which are a
thriving economy and a stable, multiparty democratic system.
</P>
<P>
The statement charged the NLD with coming up with only the
symbolic gestures designed merely to attract attention.
</P>
<P>
The government has been in the process of "exchanging views"
with a number of NLD members since September 1998 by "inviting"
them to various government guest houses, the statement said,
adding that "almost all of them have returned home after a
successful exchange of views".
</P>
<P>
The statement disclosed that there remain 55 NLD members for
continuous views exchange.
</P>
<P>
The NLD won the general election held on May 27, 1990 with 396
parliamentary seats out of 485.
</P>
<P>
On June 23, 1998, the NLD demanded the government to convene
the parliament elected in the election, setting a deadline of 60
days, but was ignored by the government.
</P>
<P>
On September 16, the NLD unilaterally formed the 10-member
"CRPP" and set up the "People's Parliament".
</P>
<P>
As for the dialogue issue between the government and the NLD,
the biggest difference is that the NLD side insists on the
inclusion in dialogue of Aung San Suu Kyi, the party's general
secretary, while the government side sticks to the exclusion of
her. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
