<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Delegation to Discuss KR Trial With Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nation will send a
delegation to Cambodia to discuss the trial of Khmer Rouge
leaders, maybe the end of July or early August, a senior un
official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the Cambodia Daily, Special Representative of
the UN Secretary-General for Human Right in Cambodia Thomas
Hammarberg said that "I have been asked about the UN's position on
the 'mixed' tribunal to try those responsible for the massive
crimes during the rule of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s."
</P>
<P>
Is a UN delegation coming to discuss this? "The answer is yes,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hammarberg said that during his meeting with Prime Minister Hun
Sen in May, the later expressed his hope that the highest
standards to be applied in the trial and experts should assist
Cambodia in drifting the legislation to ensure that it would meet
the necessary requirements.
</P>
<P>
"I conveyed this message to the UN Secretariat and proposed a
positive and quick response," said Hammarberg.
</P>
<P>
The UN Office of Legal Affairs is at present analyzing the
aspects that should be covered by the tribunal law. "It is a major
step that the UN Secretariat implicitly has declared its
willingness to support such a trial," Hammarberg said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the next step, after the finalization of the
preparations, is to agree on a date for the arrival of the UN
mission.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion I have received from New York is that they aim
for the end of July or early August," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Hammarberg said that the preparation has
taken longer than expected. The reasons, he said, are that a
"mixed" tribunal would be a new phenomenon and there is no
experience from other countries to draw on when preparing a UN
approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
