<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Kuwaiti Cabinet Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The new Kuwaiti cabinet, which
includes a mixture of old and new faces, liberal and tribal
figures, and most notably a strong economic team, was sworn in on
Wednesday before Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member cabinet was appointed by the Emir on Tuesday
following the resignation of the last cabinet ten days ago.
</P>
<P>
In the new government, which absorbed nine new comers, members
of the ruling family still hold six key posts. Former ministers of
foreign affairs, defense and interior and oil, all senior members
of the ruling family, retained their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
However, Minister of Finance and Minister of Communication
Sheikh Ali Salem Al-Ali Al-Sabah was replaced by Ahmad Abdallah
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, another royal member and a banker.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ali has reportedly lost his seat due to his pragmatism
and unpopular policies, perhaps coupled with the threat of
questioning by opposition parliament members.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of State for National Assembly Affairs,
Mohammad Deifallah Sharar succeeded Abdel Aziz Al-Dekheel as Deputy
Prime Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Other new comers included Minister of Health Dr. Mohammad
Ahmad Al-Jarallah, Minister of Justice Dr. Saad Jassem Youssef
Al-Hashel, and Minister of Information Dr. Saad Mohammad Bin
Teflah Al-Ajmi and Minister of Education and Higher Education
Dr. Youssef Hamad Al-Ibrahim, both are liberals.
</P>
<P>
Former foreign undersecretary Suleiman Majid Al-Shahin was
named the newly-created Minister of State for Foreign Affairs to
support Minister of Foreign Affairs Sheikh Sabah A-Ahmad Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Works Eid Hathal Saud Al-Rashidi is the
only elected MP selected in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of Health Adel Khaled Al-Subeih remained
in the cabinet as Minister of Electricity and Water, Minister
of State for Housing Affairs and Minister of Awqaf and
Islamic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Mohammad Bteihan Al-Dweihees, who majored in business
administration in the United States, replaced Ali Moussa
Al-Moussa as Minister of Planning and Minister of State for
Administrative Development Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Wahab Mohammad Al-Wazzan, who also received his college
education in the U.S., was named the new Minister of Commerce and
Industry, and Minister of Labor and Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's last cabinet resigned under the Constitution on July
4, after final results of the country's parliament elections were
officially announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
