<HEADLINE> PNA Agrees to Postpone Geneva Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) has agreed to postpone a U.N. sponsored conference scheduled
for Thursday to give the new Israeli government a chance to change
its policies on the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Sha'ath Wednesday told the Voice of Palestine radio that signatory
parties of the Fourth Geneva Convention are continuing their
intensive consultations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the sanctions that would be imposed on Israel
under the Geneva Conventions on the conduct of war could be
postponed another six months until the new Israeli government
practically proves its ban on settlements and land confiscation.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be held after verifying Israel's promise
which supports the convening of the conference while giving Prime
Minister Ehud Barak a chance to stop Israeli violations in the
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
He also said that all United Nations members, except the United
States and Israel, approved the convening of the conference to
examine Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the conference would take binding
resolutions against further settlement activities which will
threaten peace in the region and aim at changing the demographic
and geographic status of the Palestinian lands, especially
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israel had asked for the postponement of the Geneva
conference for six months. Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
told Israeli Radio that the conference "contravenes with the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
The postponement came after a constructive meeting between PNA
leader Yasser Arafat and Barak in the Erez Crossing Sunday. Both
sides vowed to implement all the agreements they signed and to
revive the long-deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly called last February for the
convening the meeting to ensure the Fourth Geneva Convention
on protecting civilians in occupied areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
