<HEADLINE> Former FIFA Head Respects Asian Demand for Extra Berth: Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Joao Havelange, the ex-president of
international soccer body FIFA, said he respected Asian demand of
an extra berth at the 2002 World Cup finals, according to Japan's
Kyodo news agency.
</P>
<P>
In a report filed from Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, Kyodo quoted
Havelange as saying that he understood the complexities of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
But the former chief said the AFC should realize the attention
of fans throughout the world is centered mainly on European and
South American nations.
</P>
<P>
"People would be less interested in the competition if
countries like Brazil, Argentina or Uruguay did not play the
finals," Havelange was quoted by Kyodo as saying.
</P>
<P>
Havelange pointed out that the number of European berths was
decreasing and the sacrifice of even half of a berth was not easy
for them.
</P>
<P>
"The Europeans once had 17 countries in the finals. Later, they
saw this number shrink to 16, and now only 15 European countries
can qualify for the World Cup final matches," he said.
</P>
<P>
FIFA offered the AFC a compromise deal in agreement with
European soccer body UEFA to give up half a European place to Asia.
</P>
<P>
AFC turned down the deal, saying South America could have co-
operated to offer another half a berth to the Asians.
</P>
<P>
Ten South American countries now have four and a half berths,
with a fifth placer in the qualifying round vying for a berth
against the winner of the Oceania group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
