<HEADLINE> Fewer Negative Foreign Media Reports on Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- There has been a decreasing
number of inaccurate and negative foreign media reports on
Malaysia, the House of Representatives was told Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was due to the government's proactive response and
measures in dealing with such media reports, said Deputy Foreign
Minister Leo Michael Toyad.
</P>
<P>
He said recent feedback from Malaysian missions abroad revealed
that the foreign media had started to understand the government's
stand and action in dealing with the economic and financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The measures taken by the government so far have bring
positive results," he said.
</P>
<P>
The measures include briefings on current political issues and
economic recovery efforts to target groups like foreign government
leaders, politicians, businessmen and the media itself.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry and Malaysian missions had also written to
editors of the foreign media to clarify inaccurate reports made
against Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian missions had also published newsletters to inform
Malaysian students abroad informing them of the country's policies
and developments, he said.
</P>
<P>
Programs were arranged for foreign journalists and editors to
visit Malaysia to provide them with a clearer picture of the
country's progress and development, he said. 
</P>
