<HEADLINE> Iranian Conservatives Show Strength Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's powerful conservatives
geared up their show of strength on Wednesday by staging
nationwide rallies against the student protests in the recent week.
</P>
<P>
Several millions of people from all walks of life gathered in
Tehran University and streets nearby, condemning the unrest in
the recent week, triggered by student protests to police
crackdown on student hostels.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of motor-cyclists rallied in streets of the capital
before noon, chanting slogans in support of the Islamic
revolution and upholding portraits of the late Iranian leader
Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini and Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Shouting slogans against the United States and Israel, the
demonstrators reiterated their allegiance to Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Some demonstrators presented thousands of bunches of flowers to
the police thanking their efforts to deal with rioters, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Majlis (parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-
Nouri along with a number of cabinet ministers and Majlis
deputies took part in the grand rally.
</P>
<P>
A message from Khamenei read at the rally warned that "the
powerful Islamic system will severely crush down" any riots
supported by "certain bankrupt political groups and foreign
enemies."
</P>
<P>
Along with the massive rallies throughout the country,
thousands of Basijis (military volunteers) armed with sticks and
guns have been deployed in the capital city Tehran to control the
main streets.
</P>
<P>
The rally was organized by the conservative Islamic
Propagation Organization after Khamenei warned on Monday that the
"enemies" of the Islamic system were behind the recent unrest,
the worst since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The rallies suppressed the six-day student protests to the
police unauthorized assault on the Tehran University dormitory
complex on Thursday night triggered by a student rally
protesting the newly-approved press law and the closure of the
leading moderate daily Salam (Hello).
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot police shot into the air and fired tear gas to
disperse demonstrators who claimed the police had killed at least
seven students, injured dozens and arrested hundreds of others
during the assault on student hostels.
</P>
<P>
Students demanded dismissal of the conservative police chief
Brigadier General Hedayat Lotfian, the transfer of the police
commanding power to the moderate Interior Ministry and more
freedom for press.
</P>
<P>
The student protests put more pressure on the moderate
President Mohammad Khatami to speed up his promised reforms in
the face of strong challenges from powerful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
However, diplomats and political analysts here said that the
grand rallies on Wednesday indicated a possible setback for the
Iranian reformists led by President Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
