<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Heads For Washington to Restore Trust, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak left for Washington Wednesday for his first trip to the
U.S. aimed at restoring trust and intimacy between Israel and its
closest ally and coordinating positions on reviving the stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long trip, Barak will meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton four times and discuss his plan to resume peace talks
with Syria and the Palestinians as well as Israeli-American
strategic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
After defeating former hard-line prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in the May election, Barak had initially planned to
visit the United States as the first stop of his diplomatic drive
after taking office, but Washington persuaded him to meet with
Arab leaders first.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office last Tuesday, Barak has held talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat and Jordan's King Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
These talks have been designed mainly to restore the
atmosphere of trust, which was crumbled during the three-year
tenure of Netanyahu, thus paving way for the resumption of
negotiations with the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel's ties with Washington also soured in the last three
years, with the two sides at bitter disputes over the hard-line
peace policy of the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Washington has expressed enthusiasm over the election victory
of Barak, offering help to jump-start the Middle East peace
talks, both on the Palestinian and the Syrian tracks, which were
largely frozen under Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in Florida that he was as "eager as a kid with a
new toy" to meet Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak will also meet U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who plans a shuttle diplomacy in the Middle East region
in August, including talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, the
first time in many months.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks broke off in early 1996 over the fate
of the Golan Heights, the Syrian territory seized by Israel in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Since the Israeli election in May, Syria has sent a series of
signals to Israel indicating its eagerness to resume negotiations
with Barak's new government, offering to match every peace step
Barak takes.
</P>
<P>
"The signals from Damascus in recent weeks are clearly
positive," Barak said after meeting King Abdullah in Jordan late
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
After their first summit meeting Sunday at the Erez border
crossing between Israel and the Palestinian-ruled Gaza Strip,
Barak and Arafat pledged to work together to overcome obstacles
on the road to peace.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides were at odds over Jewish settlement
expansion and the implementation of the Wye agreement, signed in
last October and then frozen by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Barak hopes to combine the implementation of Wye with the
final status talks, but Arafat demanded proper and full
implementation of the interim deal before the two sides start the
permanent negotiations.
</P>
<P>
While expected to ask for U.S. support for his negotiation
policy with the Palestinians and Syria, Barak will also seek to
reduce Washington's involvement in the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington should return to the role of "facilitator"
rather than mediator and arbitrator as it was in the negotiation
and implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
Before departing for Washington, Barak met with visiting
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel in Jerusalem, saying Israel
views its relations with Turkey as "extremely important" and these
relations pose no threat or hindrance to Israel's relations with
other countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are currently experiencing renewed momentum in the peace
process with our Arab neighbors," Barak said. "I intend to
continue this process with full determination until we reach a
comprehensive settlement."
</P>
<P>
President Demirel, the first foreign leader to visit Israel
since the launching of the new Israeli government, is on his
first leg of a regional tour, which will also take him to the
Palestinian-ruled areas and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Israel has maintained close military and economic ties with
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
