<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Lift Ban on British Beef Exports from 1 August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Farm
Commissioner Franz Fischler confirmed Wednesday that the EU is set
to lift the ban on British beef exports on August 1.
</P>
<P>
"The decision will be made in an hour and will come into force
from the first of August," Fischler told a BBC TV breakfast news
program.
</P>
<P>
The beef ban was imposed three years ago in response to
consumer fears about the spread of bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE), or the so-called "mad cow" disease.
</P>
<P>
EU veterinary experts who had insisted on stringent government
measures to reduce the risk of the BSE have given a final approval
to the lifting of the ban on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
"What has changed is very clear. First of all, we have got
positive advice from our scientists. Secondly, we did a lot of
inspections in the United Kingdom and the results are now all
positive, so it is justified now to lift the ban," Fischler said.
</P>
<P>
"If I wouldn't be convinced about that, then I would not vote
in favor to lift the ban," he said, adding that the EU is
convinced that British beef is safe under the conditions which are
in place in the future.
</P>
<P>
The lifting of the ban is expected to trigger a major marketing
campaign to regain lost export sales which have cost the British
beef industry about 2.3 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
