<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Occurs Again In Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese marine safety monitors
discovered some 6,300-sq-km of red tide yesterday in Liaodong Bay
in the northeast area of the Bohai Sea off the coast of northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the second occurrence of a large-scale red tide in the
Bohai Sea waters in a month. On July 2, 1,500-sq-km of red tide
was found in coastal waters in the western Bohai Sea and remained
there for four days.
</P>
<P>
In September and October 1998, Liaodong Bay suffered from 3,000-
sq-km of red tide for more than 20 days, causing a serious impact
on the local ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
Red tide is mainly caused by pollutants from the land and
excessive marine cultivation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
