<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Parliamentary Forum of the
Community of the Portuguese-speaking States has called on the
international community to help bring an end to the Angolan civil
war.
</P>
<P>
The forum said in its statement carried in Wednesday's Noticias
 newspaper that the international community should voice their
support for the Angolan people in search for peace in the war-torn
country and help them rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
The two-day forum, which was closed Tuesday, also discussed the
 cooperation among the seven Portuguese-speaking countries and the
 challenges they are facing in the the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has taken the place of Portugal as the president of
the forum.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting have agreed to re-locate the
headquarters of the inter-parliament organization in Mozambican
capital Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Chairman of the Assembly of the Republic, Eduardo
Mulembwe, became the executive chairman of the forum.
</P>
<P>
The forum was first established in Portuguese capital Lisbon in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Parliament heads from Mozambique, Portugal, Brazil, Angola,
Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau and Sao Tome and Principe attended the
meeting. 
