<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Probing Fraud Against Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The presidency of Nigeria has
directed the State Security Service and Nigeria Intelligence
Agency to investigate alleged fraud on qualifications by a news
magazine against Alhaji Ibrahim Buhari, speaker of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The directive is to unearth the truth behind the fraud and save
the administration from embarrassment, The Post Express newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The News magazine alleged in its cover report this week that
Buhari lied about his age and claimed educational qualifications
he did not have.
</P>
<P>
It could not be ascertained the time limit given to the two
security agencies, but their investigations are expected to be
concluded in a record time, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, members of the House from the ruling People's
Democratic Party (PDP) have set up a 10-member committee to
investigate the allegations of fraudulent claims by the Speaker.
</P>
<P>
Olisa Agbakoba of Senior Advocate of Nigeria and Abdul Oroh,
executive director of Civil Liberties Organization have called on
the Speaker to step down to give room for unimpeded investigation
into the matter.
</P>
<P>
Deputy leader of the House of Representative Chief Mao
Chuabunwa disclosed the setting up of an investigation panel,
adding that the ruling party decided to take the step because the
allegations were too grave to be ignored.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that if the House confirmed that what the
magazine wrote about the Speaker was true, a motion could be moved
to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
However, Deputy Speaker of the House Chibudum Nwoche described
the allegations as "politically motivated", hence the allegations
should be discountenanced.
</P>
<P>
He said, "what we saw in the magazine were the same things we
saw during the campaign," but he added, "if we confirm that the
allegations are true, it is left for us to move a motion."
</P>
<P>
Senator Tokunbo Afikuyomi, member of the Alliance for Democracy
(AD) representing Lagos Central Senatorial District said that he
had confirmed from Toronto University of Canada, where the Speaker
claimed to have graduated from, his name could not be found in the
university's record.
</P>
<P>
According to the senator, "it is not only the integrity of the
Speaker that is at stake, but also the whole National Assembly and
the Fourth Republic."
</P>
<P>
Olisa Agbakoba noted that the incident is a test case for the
Obasanjo administration and advised the Speaker to step down to
allow uninfringed investigation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued on Tuesday by the press office to the
Speaker said that the Speaker had briefed his solicitor Chief
F.R.A. Williams on taking appropriate steps against the magazine.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the solicitor has given the
magazine a 72- hour ultimatum to retract and render an unreserved
apology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
