<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Vows to Curb Speculators' Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada assured
the public Wednesday that his economic team is ready to foil any
move by currency speculators in manipulating the movement of the
peso in the market.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said newly-appointed Governor Rafael Buenaventura of
the Philippine Central Bank, as well as the rest of his economic
team, is now crafting measures to thwart this "get-rich-quick"
scheme of speculators.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot discount the activity of these speculators who want
to earn a fast buck. That's why I warned them so that their moves
won't affect our economy," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
From last Friday's 38.50, the peso continued to appreciate
against the U.S. dollar, with Tuesday's trading closing at 38.34
to one dollar following the warning aired by the president and his
economic managers against speculators in a regular TV program.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said the president also called on Filipino
businessmen to join forces with government in sustaining the
country's status as the leader in economic recovery among Asian
crisis-hit economies, instead of engaging in currency speculation
and other unethical trade practices.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president noted that the foreign exchange reserve
was at an all-time high of 14 billion dollars, making it easier
for the Central Bank to counter any pressure on the peso
investigated by currency speculators.
</P>
<P>
When the peso suffered a sharp fall last year, the country's
foreign exchange reserves reportedly amounted to less than 8
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
