<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Takes Steps to Stamp out Unfair Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan state minister in charge
of planning and investment Gabriel Opio has assured investors that
the government is committed to stamping out unfair trade and
irregularities, a local report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Opio was in reaction to a foreign company's report that without
firmer and more even-handed implementation of government
regulation, the climate does not encourage further investment in
the local textile sector.
</P>
<P>
The state minister said in a statement that the strengthening
of the Uganda Revenue Authority administration and management
systems together with the real rationalization of anti-smuggling,
dumping and corruption, will ensure growth of the country's
textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Other measures, he said, included legalizing the awarding of 10
percent commission to informers of smuggling activities and tax
evasion and increased funding for the Auditor General by 39
percent and for Inspector General of the Government by 47 percent
in this financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
