<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Arrives in Baghdad to Close UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. technical team to remove
toxic chemical substances left behind in the Baghdad laboratory of
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq arrived in
Baghdad on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, sent by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and
led by South Africa's chemical production technologist Dirk van
Niekerk, is to meet Annan's special representative in Baghdad
Prakash Shah and three senior diplomats from the Chinese, Russian
and French embassies in Baghdad before it will carry out its
mission.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team comprises four chemical experts from the
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons in the Hague
and an independent biological weapons expert.
</P>
<P>
These U.N. experts are from China, Russia, Poland and
Germany. Yako Yalato, a Finnish, former Assistant Director of
U.N. Baghdad Monitoring and Verification Center, will act as
guide for the technical team.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. reached an agreement last month on the
composition of the technical team to visit UNSCOM's Baghdad
laboratory, where one kilogram of mustard gas and VX gas were left
behind by UNSCOM before it withdrew from Iraq last December.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not resumed its work of weapons inspections in Iraq
since last December when the United States and Britain launched
four-night airstrikes against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Again Leads Global Competitiveness List: WEF Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 14 (Xinhua)-- Singapore once again ranks as the
world's most competitive country despite the impact of the Asian
financial crisis, according to a recent report issued by the
Geneva-based World Economic Forum (WEF).
</P>
<P>
The United States, the third in last year's ranking, has
elbowed out Hong Kong to rank second while Hong Kong dropped to
third, the Global Competitiveness Report said.
</P>
<P>
The report measures such variables as government regulations
and technology conditions to decide which economies have the best
ability to grow rapidly in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth time that the report has placed Singapore
top-notch in its most-competitive-country list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0156 </DOCNO>
