<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Train Filipino Seaman Computer Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has taken
fresh steps to make the sailors computer literate so as to further
sharpen their global competitiveness, a senior official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government has introduced a new computer literacy course
for seamen to better comply with the Standards of Training
Certification and Watchkeeping Convention, a requirement for a
country to be appreciated by the International Maritime
Organization, said Reynaldo Regalado, chief of the Philippine
Overseas Employment Administration (POEA).
</P>
<P>
Last month, President Joseph Estrada ordered the Overseas
Workers Welfare Administration, the POEA and other government
agencies concerned to intensify efforts to improve the seamen's
skills in this front.
</P>
<P>
A total of 49,515 Filipino seamen were deployed abroad from
January to April this year, slightly higher than the 48,373
sailors who went overseas in the same period of 1998, according to
POEA records.
</P>
<P>
Regalado said the new computer course for seafarers, which was
developed by the National Maritime Polytechnic School last summer,
was tailored for the facilities of a high-tech ship.
</P>
<P>
This course, he said, covers concepts on information processing
systems computer organization, operating systems and application
systems software, networking concepts and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a maritime mission led by Labor Secretary Bienvenido
Laguesma received assurance from maritime employers in five
European countries -- Greece, Sweden, Norway, the United Kingdom
and the Netherlands -- that they would continue hiring
Philippines' seafarers to man their ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
