<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's E-commerce Applications Markets to Expand Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific market for
Internet commerce applications has been enjoying a robust growth
over the past year, and will likely remain that way through 2003,
according to a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Internet commerce application software enables companies to
conduct business on-line. The Asia-Pacific market, excluding Japan,
topped 20.1 million U.S. dollars in revenue in 1998, up 104
percent from a year ago, said the U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The IDC estimates a 95 percent growth to 40.45 million dollars
this year and 167.76 million dollars in 2000. By 2003, the market
is projected to top 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDC, two types of software should warrant
special attention over the next two years. One application allows
Web sites to better manage on-line content; the other helps sites
improve their interaction with customers. Both will be
increasingly important to companies betting their future on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The IDC expects to see a tremendous growth in the number of E-
commerce software vendors indigenous to the region, providing
multilingual, business-to-business and business-to-consumer
software applications in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Technology localization will be the key success factor of
penetrating the Asian markets, the IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Right now Australia and New Zealand are the leading driver of
sales for E-commerce software vendors in the region. This is
mainly a result of the use of English as the main language medium,
a relatively mature information technology infrastructure and high
Internet user penetration. In addition, the hottest markets for E-
commerce software adoption among innovative companies are
Singapore, Malaysia, South Korea and Taiwan, the IDC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
