<HEADLINE> Barak Vows to Abide by Agreements With Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
pledged to comply with all agreements his country had signed with
the Palestinians as part of the efforts to revive the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the pledge Tuesday night during his talks with
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein at the southern port city of
Aqaba of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Barak also voiced hope to resume Israel's
peace talks with Syria and he said, without elaborating, that
Damascus had sent "very positive signals" on the peace talks last
week, the semi-official Jordan Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak paid a brief visit to Jordan Tuesday before heading for
Washington for a summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton on reviving
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak briefed Abdullah on the outcome of his just-concluded
talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat during which he renewed commitments to peace
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to what he described as a key role in the
peace process played by Jordan under King Abdullah and late King
Hussein Bin Talal, Abdullah's father who died of cancer in
February.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral ties, Barak said he and Jordanian leaders had
discussed trade projects, the issue of building a joint airport
in Aqaba and water-sharing issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This was Barak's first visit to Jordan after he won a landslide
victory in the May 17 election which brought down his hard-line
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu from the Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Israel's peace talks with the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon
remained virtually deadlocked during Netanyahu's three years in
office.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and other Arab countries have pinned hopes on Barak
to recommit Israel to peace in the region and to resume
peace talks with all Arab neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
