<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Support Anyone Who Becomes Indonesian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Regarding the result of the
successful general election process in Indonesia, the European
Union (EU) said Wednesday it will support anyone who becomes the
legitimate president of Indonesia regardless of it is a she or a
he.
</P>
<P>
Hannu Himanen, representative of the EU Presidency, said here
that the EU will respect the democratic process in the country
"working in such way," and the Indonesian people and the elected
legislative representatives have a right to decide who governs the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Any legitimate Indonesian government led by an elected
president will be a partner for the European Union," he said after
the final press conference on the European Union Observation Unit.
</P>
<P>
Himanen, who is also the ambassador of Finland to Indonesia,
said that the EU will continue and intensify cooperation with the
country's next president and government.
</P>
<P>
In observing the June 7 general election, at least 30 long-term
observers who arrived in Jakarta on May 12 were deployed in 14
provinces, not to mention some 90 short-term observers who were
deployed for 15 days during the preparations for and after the
election around the country except the provinces of Aceh, Irian
Jaya, East Timor and West Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
The EU contributed 7.7 million U.S. dollars for the electoral
process, channeled through the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Chief Observer/Executive Coordinator of the EU observer unit
John Gwyn Morgan said at the press conference that the general
election in Indonesia was smooth, fair and transparent, despite
several minor cases.
</P>
<P>
"We are reporting the result of our observation during the
general election in this country to our headquarters in Brussels,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Morgan said the EU will support individuals who become the
president, not certain parties.
</P>
<P>
"The EU recognizes the individual president who is the result
of the democratic process in this country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Beside Megawati Soekarnoputri, leader of the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle, and incumbent President B.J.
Habibie, several names like Armed Forces Commander General
Wiranto, Chairman of the People's Mandate Party Amien Rais and
Chairman of Nahdlatul Ulama Abdurrahman Wahid have been nominated
as candidates for the next president.
</P>
<P>
The People's Consultative Assembly, Indonesia's highest
decision-making body, will meet in November to elect the country's
next president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
