<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Feature) World Bank Loan to Help Alleviate Poverty in Western China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Cang Soinan, a Tibetan farmer in
eastern Qinghai Province, works hard in double harness with his
wife all year round on his 0.8 hectares of land, but they find it
difficult to feed themselves for a quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
"We harvest only 800 kg of grain in ordinary years since our
fields are inferior and in a hilly and arid area. If there is a
drought, we reap almost nothing and have to live on government
relief," he said.
</P>
<P>
The couple live in a three-room house made of sun-dried mud
bricks. They have no cattle or sheep nor a single piece of decent
furniture. All they have is a double bed and two cupboards.
</P>
<P>
"The government is preparing to help us move to a vast fertile
land in Dulan County in the Mongolian-Tibetan Autonomous
Prefecture of Haixi. Only by leaving this unproductive land can we
have a bright future," she said.
</P>
<P>
This expresses the ardent hope of poor people living in eastern
Qinghai, a multi-ethnic region on the northeastern tip of the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, known as the "Roof of the World." The
plateau covers an area of 721,200 square kilometers, making it
fourth in area after the autonomous regions of Xinjiang, Tibet,
and Inner Mongolia. Eastern Qinghai is densely populated and has a
harsh and arid environment resulting in low crop output. A great
number of farmers and herdsmen there still live below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
To lift these people out of poverty, the provincial government
plans to move 57,000 farmers from six over-farmed counties in
Haidong Prefecture in eastern Qinghai to Balong and Zongjia
townships in Dulan County where 366,000 hectares of arable land
remain to be opened up, and four rivers are nearby. The immigrants
comprise people of the Han, Hui, Tibetan, Tu and Salar.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of a poverty-relief program implemented by
the land-locked province, and implementation of this project will
effectively alleviate the destruction of vegetation and curb soil
erosion in Qinghai, said Guanbo, an official of the soon-to-be
settled area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Feature) World Bank Loan to Help Alleviate Poverty in Western China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The funds will be used to plant trees and grass on 5,300
hectares of land, open up 21,300 hectares of wasteland, set up 126
resettlement villages in four townships, and build two reservoirs,
two power stations, 11 schools and 22 hospitals and clinics. A
national highway trunk road will be extended to Dulan County in
central Qinghai to facilitate trade and economic growth there.
</P>
<P>
The projected new area has for centuries been populated by
Mongolian herdsmen, and became a multi-ethnic area predominantly
inhabited by Mongolians when people of the Han and other ethnic
groups settled there a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
At present, the area is sparsely populated with only 5,736
residents. Mongolians number 3,717, accounting for 54 percent of
the total population, and the Han inhabitants totals 2,111, or 36.
8 percent. There are also 276 Tibetans, or 4.8 percent, and the
remainder are people of the Hui and Tu.
</P>
<P>
When the 57,000 immigrants are settled, the ratio of people of
the Han in the region will drop by five percent, and that of the
Mongolian people is expected to decline by one percentage point
because no more Mongolians are expected to move in.
</P>
<P>
The number of Tibetans will increase from 276 to 3,700, with
its ratio of the local population rising from 4.8 to six percent.
People of other ethnic groups will also rise to varying extents,
said Gao Hui'en, an official with the Qinghai Provincial Office
for Foreign-funded Projects of Poverty Alleviation and Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
