<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Keep Gold Reserves Untouched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese government has expressed
that it would not touch the country's gold reserves even though
the world's gold price is expected to drop further.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon will not sell off its gold reserves which is
considered one of the Lebanese economy's elements of strength,"
Prime Minister Salim Hoss said Tuesday at a parliament session,
the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He was answering the question by parliament members over the
possibility of unloading million ounces of bullion to deal with
the fluctuating world gold market.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold sank last week to less than 256 U.S. dollars
an ounce for the first time for 20 years after the Bank of England
sold off massive amounts of its gold bullion.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices threatened to plummet further as dealers and
analysts speculated that other nations might unload their reserves.
</P>
<P>
Riad Salmeh, Lebanese Central Bank governor, estimated the
price of Lebanon's gold stocks at 2.8 billion dollars, down from
the 1993 peak of 3.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gold was bought in the 1960s to support the
Lebanese pound.
</P>
<P>
"The use of gold to back the national currency is an internal
part of national security and not subject to the laws of the
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Lebanon should keep its gold and give the
Central Bank some freedom in administering it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges More Debt Relief for Poor Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Jubilee 2000-Zambia Campaign,
part of a world-wide anti-debt drive, has urged industrialized
countries to relieve more debt from poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The organization said in a statement issued in Lusaka Tuesday
that the recently announced package for debt relief under the G-7
initiative is not enough to make significant changes.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Wednesday quoted the statement
as saying that most poor countries will continue to pay more than
20 percent of government revenue toward servicing their foreign
debts even with the amnesty pledged by the G-7 industrialized
countries at their meeting in Cologne, Germany, last June.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee 2000-Zambia coordinator Barbara Kalima said the
framework under the G-7 debt initiative would only relieve Zambia
of about 900 million U.S. dollars from the stock of six billion
dollars in foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
This calls for vigorous campaign to achieve significant debt
cancellation that will improve people's life, Kalima said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that her organization, in collaboration with other
civic groups like trade union, students' and women's groups and
individuals, will fight for economic and social justice to improve
the living of the Zambians living in abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, considering Zambia's population of about 10
million, the immense debt burden means that every woman, man and
child owes 650 dollars to international creditors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the southern African country spends 200 million
dollars annually on debt servicing, and is likely to be faced with
over 600-million- dollar annual debt servicing bills after the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
