<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Feature) World Bank Loan to Help Alleviate Poverty in Western China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Konbu Dangzhou, a Tibetan farmer in Balong Township of Dulan
County, said, "Life has changed a lot since my family moved here
from a hilly area in eastern Qinghai 10 years ago."
</P>
<P>
"We were given 1.5 hectares of land on which we built a 10-room
house with a courtyard and grew grain crops and vegetables. the
average annual net profit gained from grain production now exceeds
20,000 yuan, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The family has bought a tractor and a seeder and flour-milling
machine, and their house is equipped with modern furniture and a
full array of household appliances including a TV and VCD.
</P>
<P>
"Farm work in the village has been mechanized. When more
immigrants come here, I'll open a farm tool repair shop."
</P>
<P>
"The status of Mongolians and Tibetans will remain unchanged
and so will the regions inhabited by various ethnic groups," Gao
Gui'en said.
</P>
<P>
The wishes of the ethnic groups will be respected in the course
of settlement. Tibetans will live in a separate area near villages
inhabited by the Tu because they share similar customs and
religion -- Tibetan Buddhism. The Salar people will be placed in
an area next to Hui people because they share a belief in Islam.
Those who wish to live together with other ethnic groups may live
in a multi-ethnic area.
</P>
<P>
In this way, Gao said, all ethnic groups will retain their
existing modes of production, customs and habits, religious
beliefs and the traditional education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
