<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Global Competitiveness Listing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa was ranked the
47th in terms of competitiveness, dropping five places from last
year's global listing, and was seen by global executives as one of
the five least secure countries of the 59 surveyed in this year's
study.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 edition of the Global Competitiveness Report,
published yearly by the World Economic Forum and the Harvard
Institute for International Development, placed South Africa last
in terms of labor practices such as firing and hiring workers,
labor relations, work ethic and labor regulations.
</P>
<P>
The report, published by the Business Day newspaper Wednesday,
said that the labor component of the competitiveness index, which
is made up of eight indicators, seeks to measure the efficiency
(ease of hiring and sacking workers) and competitiveness of the
country's labor market, including costs relative to international
norms.
</P>
<P>
Other indicators making up the competitiveness index are
management, institutions, the state's role in the economy, the
trade and investment regime as well as infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The index seeks to show that competitive countries are those
that have underlying economic conditions to achieve rapid growth
over a number of years, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The study forecasts that South Africa, ranked the 45th in
growth terms, will have 2.3 percent annual gross domestic product
growth per capita in the period from the year 2000 to 2008.
</P>
<P>
This year's study added six more countries, with Mauritius
making its debut in the 29th position. Zimbabwe slipped to the
57th position from the 51st slot it occupied in 1997 and last
year.
</P>
<P>
The study noted that poor performers like Zimbabwe are
characterized by low rule of law, uncertainty of property rights
and poor infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Singapore maintained its leading position as the most
competitive country ranked, with Russia taking the dubious honor
of being the least competitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
