<HEADLINE> Two Shanghai Cyclists Arrive in Qinghai En Route To Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Two elderly men from Shanghai have
arrived on their bicycles at the Qaidam Basin in northwest China's
Qinghai province on their way to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Lin Zhiyou and Xu Guoqiang, together with four others, began
their Shanghai-Lhasa bicycle tour from Shanghai on May 18.
</P>
<P>
So far they have traveled through seven provinces including
Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Anhui, Henan, Shaanxi, Ningxia, and Gansu,
covering some 5,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The six are all members of the Shanghai Bicycle Tourists'
Association, with the youngest aged 62 and the oldest 68.
</P>
<P>
Lin and Xu told Xinhua they plan to meet their four other
partners in the Golmud City of the province, and then cycle along
the Qinghai-Tibet Highway to Lhasa, capital of southwest China's
Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
They said they plan to arrive at their destination at the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
This year has been designated the Year of the Aged, and it is
also the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic
of China, the 40th anniversary of Tibet's Democratic Reform, and
the year of Macao's return to China.
</P>
<P>
That is why they chose this year for their tour, Lin said,
adding that they found the trip meaningful and enjoyable despite
some hardships.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he is very grateful to people they are meeting
along their way who often offer accommodations and assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
