<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expedition Ship Enters Arctic Circle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese expedition ship
Snow Dragon carrying more than 120 scientists and journalists
entered the Arctic Circle today at 0:38 Beijing time.
</P>
<P>
The expedition team began their scientific research today at
the Chukchi Sea, and the ship is expected to enter the floating
ice area of the Arctic Ocean tomorrow, said Qin Weijia, assistant
to the chief expedition scientist.
</P>
<P>
The ocean and weather conditions over the two weeks of the
voyage have been most conducive to scientific observations and
research, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, the team members have been experiencing longer
days and shorter nights as the ship nears the North Pole, with the
temperature hovering at about one degree C.
</P>
<P>
Xie Simei, a team meteorologist, said nephograms received on
the ship show that the sea ice is diminishing above 71 degrees
north latitude, a good indication for a smooth voyage.
</P>
<P>
Some floating ice can be seen near the ship, and visibility
will be five to ten nautical miles, according to weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Dragon, a modern icebreaker carrying scientists and
journalists, left Shanghai on July 1. This is China's first
expedition to the North Pole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
