<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000-Year Old Cultural Site Discovered in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered a cultural site dating back to the late New Stone Age
of 4,000 years ago in Yudu County in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, several local farmers unearthed a quantity
of pottery pieces covered with strange patterns in the Kuanshizhai
area in southern Yudu County. The discovery soon stirred the
interest of archeologists, who then conducted excavations of the
area.
</P>
<P>
They have so far unearthed refined stone articles and 50 pieces
of pottery including red pottery jars, kettles and cooking vessel.
</P>
<P>
The markings on these pieces consist of knots, circles,
bowstrings, and weaving patterns.
</P>
<P>
This discovery indicates human presence in the area 4,000 years
ago, said one archeologist, adding that the site will provide
valuable material for the study of the culture and history of
southern Jiangxi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
