<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Prepares for Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan National Year 2000
(Y2K) Task Force is determined to complete the Y2K preparedness
efforts on time, the task force has said.
</P>
<P>
Local media Wednesday quoted a report of the task force as
saying that as a result of the National Task Force vigilance, "our
vision of 'life as normal' during the millennium date changes will
be attained in Uganda."
</P>
<P>
The report concentrates on critical sectors including aviation,
 electricity, oil supply, telecommunications, banking, revenue
collections and water and sewerage.
</P>
<P>
It examines the status of the plans and the actual Y2K
remediation work that has been completed.
</P>
<P>
It warns that three major dates may cause problems in old
computer systems: September 9, 1999 which may be interpreted as a
null date; January 1, 2000 which may be recognized as January 1,
1999 and February 20, 2000 which may not be recognized as a valid
leap year date.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K status assessment was done using the standard COMPARE
(Compliance Progress And Readiness) methodology used by the
Cartner Group in their Y2K testimony in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan national Y2K task force was set up in January, 1999
to spearhead the national effort in dealing with the Y2K problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surging Demand in Telecom Industry to Drive Semiconductor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The current up-cycle for the
semiconductor and related industries worldwide could last as long
as seven years.
</P>
<P>
Instead of personal computers (PC) sales, the predicted growth
will come from the world's telecommunications sector, which is
rushing to keep up with demand created by the rising popularity of
the Internet and shift to global business networking models.
</P>
<P>
These views were offered by Fred Zieber, president of
Pathfinder Research, a U.S. high-tech business consulting and
market analysis firm focusing on most aspects of the chip industry.
He was speaking Tuesday at the annual exposition in San Francisco
hosted by trade association Semiconductor Equipment and Materials
International (SEMI)
</P>
<P>
SEMI members supply the equipment and materials used to make
semiconductors, or chips, the brains behind everything from
automobiles to wireless telephones. The industry is experiencing a
turnaround after a sharp downturn in 1998.
</P>
<P>
SEMI quoted Zieber as saying that the current up-cycle reflects
the revolution taking place in telecommunications, and more
specifically the Internet and World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
The chip equipment and materials industry's old reliable source
of revenues and profits, the PC, won't be driving the surge in
sales as the upswing progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications should be a large market, but is only a
fraction of the size of the PC market. Meanwhile, Zieber noted,
sales of PCs are slowing at the time their prices are falling.
</P>
<P>
According to a new report released Monday, SEMI members
predicted that worldwide semiconductor equipment sales in 1999
will reach 23.8 billion U.S. dollars, up nine percent from a year
ago. Last year, the market decreased almost 21 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
