<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Environment on Verge of Collapse: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- In the near future, Israelis
will have to go abroad if they want to enjoy nature or even a
clean beach, the local daily Jerusalem Post quoted a report on
the country's environment as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prepared by more than 100 scientists and experts, the report
declared that Israel's environment is "on the verge of collapse,"
citing irreversible salification of underground aquifers, declining
quality of air, piling-up of garbage and uncontrolled construction
which is eating away at open areas.
</P>
<P>
Besides issuing warnings, the report also sets new priorities
for dealing with the environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
Arguing the common claim that little can be done to improve
the environment without major capital investment, the report said
changes do not necessarily require massive government budgets.
</P>
<P>
It suggests that the government promote environmental awareness
and education, initiate legislation relating to land use, adopt
stricter European standards for vehicle emissions, and improve
public transportation by setting aside additional bus lanes.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends the establishment of a "popular lobby
for the environment" that would be alert to threats facing the
environment and press for immediate action.
</P>
<P>
Finally, "the polluter must pay" should become a rule, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Environment Ministry said he had asked
ministry experts to study the report and the ministry will
deal with it seriously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
