<HEADLINE> Australian Sports Minister Warns off Olympic Drugs Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian Sports Minister Jackie
Kelly unveiled the results of the latest drug-testing research on
Wednesday and warned drugs cheats to stay away from the 2000
Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Sydney, The Australian government has
committed three million dollars for research into substances such
as erythropoetin, or EPO, which is the latest rage among sportsmen
looking for a short cut to success.
</P>
<P>
It increases production of oxygen-carrying red blood cells,
which improve stamina.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very confident that the IOC will support any move to show
that the Sydney 2000 Games are the cleanest Games ever," Kelly
said on a tour of the Australian Sports Drug Testing Laboratory (
ASDTL) where 2,000 drug tests will be carried out during the Games.
</P>
<P>
She said Jacques Rogge, chairman of the IOC Coordination
Commission monitoring Sydney's progress, had told her the test
would be included if they could satisfy the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Kelly said: "I'm warning the athletes who think they could
still be using it coming to Sydney ... really think again."
</P>
<P>
She warned that "By July 2000 you want to be very, very, very
clean. Don't enter Australia and think that you can rob athletes
of medals." 
</P>
</TEXT>
