<HEADLINE> Singapore Firm Told to Pay for Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Dong Ya Tankers (PTE) Ltd. of
Singapore was recently instructed by a court ruling to pay more
than three million yuan to the Maritime Administration of
Guangdong Province in compensation for an oil spill and attendant
damages they were found to be responsible for.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, in February 1997, the fully loaded
Ocean Success, an oil tanker owned by the Singaporean company, was
in Zhanjiang Port of the southern China province for unloading
operations.
</P>
<P>
Due to a major failure in one of the tanker's valves, 300 tons
of crude oil was poured into the sea, seriously polluting the
water and seabed of Zhanjiang Port as well as the ecological
environment of nearby tidal zones, and destroying natural fishing
resources in the area.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province entered a lawsuit in the Guangzhou Maritime
Court asking the Singaporean company to pay 16 million yuan in
compensation for the oil leakage and damages.
</P>
<P>
After an investigation, the court found the Dong Ya Tankers Ltd.
responsible for the oil spill and ordered that the company pay 3.1
million yuan in compensation and another 350,000 yuan to cover
expenditures related to the incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Ends Annual Review in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund's
(IMF) mission has ended its annual review of Kenya's economy, but
will not present its report to the IMF board for three months to
allow Nairobi to implement some of its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The eight-man mission, which left here Tuesday, had reviewed
Kenya's fiscal and monetary issues, the banking sector, the
privatization of state- run companies and the efforts to reduced
the bloated civil service, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF halted its three-year 205-million-U.S.-dollar loan
package in July, 1997 to reinforce its protests against corruption
and poor governance in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, informal talks between the IMF and the
Kenyan government have failed to yield a resumption of formal
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
During their stay here, the IMF officials examined such
governance issues earlier proposed as the operations of the Kenya
Anti-Corruption Authorities and transparent tendering procedures.
</P>
<P>
Governor Micah Cheserem of the Kenya's Central Bank said that
the offer to hold its report to the board for three months by the
mission would allow action on some of its recommendations and move
Kenya closer to formal loan negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Since the suspension of the IMF loan in 1997, Kenya's economy
has been worsening with the growth rate sliding down to 1.8
percent in 1998 from 4.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya has forecast gross domestic product
growth rate at two percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, independent economists said that a decline in all
sectors of the economy will lead to growth of between zero and 1.4
percent and any other predictions are too optimistic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
