<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Visit to Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
left here Wednesday for a three-day official visit to Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule territories and Jordan with a view to
advancing the Mideast Peace process.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the Ankara Esenboga Airport that Turkey
always encourages efforts aimed at securing peace, stability and
prosperity in the Middle East in a decisive and active way.
</P>
<P>
Demirel is expected to visit Israel on July 14-15, and the
Palestinian territories and Jordan on July 16.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Mideast Peace process, which has been
stalled due to the hard-line policies pursed by former Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, is facing a golden opportunity
which might slip away.
</P>
<P>
However, Demirel added that in the elections in Israel, a great
majority of the people voted for the continuation of the process,
according to local Daily News Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit to Israel is aimed at further enhancing
Turkey's growing ties with this country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have signed a series of military cooperation
agreements, causing great panic among the Arab states and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Demirel reiterated that Turkey's ties with Israel are not
directed against any other regional country and that the growing
relations with the Jewish state "should be taken into
consideration that is under way in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Syria has exploited the relations between
Turkey and Israel and turned the Arab countries against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, he stated that Turkey does not need Israel to cope
with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
"We have no need for Israel to deal with Syria. This is out of
the question," he said, adding "Turkey is a strong country. Our
relations with Israel should not be regarded as an alliance."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
