<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Position on Taiwan Unchanged: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman
Sadaaki Numata said Tuesday that Japan's position on Taiwan
remains unchanged and Japan's relationship with the island is of
non-governmental nature.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the recent separatist remarks of Taiwan's
Lee Teng-hui, Numata told a regular press conference that Japan
will firmly maintain its position expressed in the 1972 Japan-
China Joint Statement, in which Tokyo says that it fully
understands and respects the Chinese government's stand that
Taiwan is an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
Lee said in an interview with a German radio station on July 9
that cross-straits relations should be defined as "state-to-state
or at least special state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
Japan strongly hopes that the Taiwan issue would be settled
peacefully through direct dialog between the two sides across the
Taiwan Strait, the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
