<HEADLINE> India's Steel Imports, Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- India's steel imports rose 29
percent in April and May, the first two months of the new fiscal
year, according to the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Steel user industries and traders purchased 160,000 tons of
steel in April and May this year, compared to 124,000 tons during
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase in steel imports this year comes in the wake of an
equally dramatic drop in imports last year and despite the import
ban on the cheap metal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's steel exports sprang up by 17 percent.
Enthused by the slight increase in steel prices in the world
market, steel producers at home shipped out 319,000 tons of steel
in April and May as against 273,000 tons in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Steel imports stood at 1.48 million tons last year, a 25
percent decrease from the previous year's 1.85 million tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenic-Related Diseases Wide-Spread in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Arsenic-related diseases have taken
on an epidemic form in Bangladesh's 21 districts claiming the
lives of hundreds of people, the Independent daily newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The zonal headquarters of the Public Health in the Khulna
division, about 140 kilometers southwest of here, had undertaken a
comprehensive water test with a view to identifying
arsenic-contaminated tube-wells in these 21 districts and found
all the tube-wells of the Khulna Police Lines had been arsenic
polluted, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Finding no other alternative, the vast population in these
areas was using arsenic-contaminated water as the people did not
have enough money to purchase deep tube-wells that cost 5,000 taka
(about 103.1 U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
In many areas, arsenic was found above the acceptable level of
0.01 to 0.05 percent per liter of water, and in some cases the
level rose to 3 percent per liter, Mohammad Abdus Sattar, a senior
chemist of the Khulna Public Health office, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is the main reason for the wide-spread arsenic-related
diseases in these districts.
</P>
<P>
An alarming situation was prevailing in Khulna division
especially Khulna city and adjoining areas.
</P>
<P>
The patients with arsenic-related disease are initially found
to have some skin diseases in the hands and legs, but ultimately
their kidneys and livers are damaged and with the failure of these
two vital organs, they die soon, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the UNICEF (United Nations International
Children's Emergency Fund), Japan and the Netherlands are working
to mitigate the sufferings of the people through non-government
organizations in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Arsenic, a deadly mineral in water, has so far attacked as many
as 59 out of Bangladesh's 64 districts, Minister of Local
Government and Rural Development Zillur Rahman said in the
parliament in early February.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh suffers most seriously from arsenic pollution in the
world and the government has already taken a series of measures to
control arsenic contamination.
</P>
<P>
The government approved a non-government organizational
emergency project to supply pure water, which was launched at a
cost of 1.79 billion taka (about 36.9 million dollars) in February
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
