<HEADLINE> 14 Zimbabwean Demonstrators Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 demonstrating
Zimbabwean ex-combatants were arrested in Harare Tuesday,
following running battles with riot police, the daily Herald
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators had gathered at the ruling party headquarters
to press for the payment of 500,000 Zimbabwean dollars (13,000
U.S. dollars), among other demands, for the part they played
during the war of liberation.
</P>
<P>
All the arrested demonstrators were women who had failed to run
away from the advancing riot police and sought refuge at the
headquarters of the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union
(Patriotic Front).
</P>
<P>
Riot police fired tear gas to disperse the demonstrators after
they had locked the gates to the building.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Zimbabwe National War Veterans'
Association Endy Mhlanga condemned the police action, saying that
they provoked an otherwise peaceful demonstration by his members
who wanted to be paid what they were promised.
</P>
<P>
"The tear-gassing of peaceful demonstrators is not fair. They
should have been left to express their dissatisfaction on the
manner things concerning them are being handled," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
