<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Fabric Exports Expected to Grow at 16 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian fabric exports are
expected to grow at a compound annual rate of 16 percent till the
year 2001/02, according to a Crisil study published on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Crisil report predicts that the country's cotton fabric
exports will grow at an annualized 15 percent through to 2001/02,
while synthetic and blended fabric exports are expected to
increase by an annualized 20 percent in this period.
</P>
<P>
The overall fabric demand, both domestic and for exports, is
likely to record a compound annual growth rate of about 8.5
percent to reach 50 billion square meters in the year 2001/02. The
share of exports in the total fabric demand is likely to increase
from 18 percent in 1997/98 to about 24 percent in 2001/02.
</P>
<P>
The increased export demand is expected as a result of the
phasing-out of capacities in the developed world, and increased
market access following the gradual dismantling of quotas of the
United States and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
