<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More State Enterprises to be Privatized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Eleven more state-owned economic
enterprises (SEEs) in different parts of Myanmar will be
privatized by being sold through competitive bidding to national
entrepreneurs, The Mirror official newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 11 SEEs include two soft drink and ice-making plants in
Nyaunglaybin township, and nine rice mills in Minpya, Hinthada,
Mawlamyine, Bago, Thandwe, Letpadan and Pyay townships.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises to be auctioned also include those nationalized
in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for the submission of bidding is set on August 13,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the Myanmar government's
Privatization Commission privatized a total of 74 SEEs, which
include four factories, 7 rice mills, 57 cinemas and 6 hotels.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has, since January 1995, been implementing a
privatization plan for its SEEs, aimed at transforming them into
effective business organizations.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the scheme covers 51 SEEs including
processing and manufacturing factories, livestock breeding farms
and cinemas, and has been implemented in various ways --
auctioning and leasing out the enterprises or establishing joint
ventures with local and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
In a significant move to accelerate the privatization of heavy
industries, Myanmar transferred to local private entrepreneurs the
Ywama steel mill in September 1998, the biggest SEE leased out
after the privatization plan began.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there is a total of 36,275
private industrial enterprises in Myanmar by the end of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
