<HEADLINE> Romanian President Criticizes Western Economic Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 13 (Xinhua) -- President Emil Constantinescu
said Tuesday NATO's air campaign and EU's sanctions against
Yugoslavia have imposed heavy economic losses on Romania and what
his country badly needs is substantive support, not empty promises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Romania-U.S. Action Committee meeting held here,
Constantinescu explicitly expressed his dissatisfaction at the
rigid conditions western countries attach on their provision of
loans to his country, reported Antenna One television.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that when NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia
ended, senior delegations from the European Union and NATO visited
Bucharest one after another. However, they only expressed thanks
for Romania's unconditional support to NATO during its eleven-week
airstrike but were vague on substantive issues such as Romania's
security guarantees and economic compensations.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the economic cooperation between Romania and the
United States, Constantinescu said there is hardly any U.S.
investment in Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian leader held out hope that western countries would
not order Romania about and raise contradictory requests. He said
while the World Bank urged Romania to step up economic reform and
investors from the west wanted Romania to improve investment
environment, the International Monetary Fund demanded Romania
maintain its macro economic stability and revoke its preferential
tax policy toward foreign capital.
</P>
