<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Headway In Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua)-- China made remarkable progress in
restructuring its economy and optimizing industrial mix in the
first half of this year, according to the State Economic and Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
In the sweeping move, quite a few large enterprise groups were
established, while dozens of other firms were shaped into
companies in accordance with the Company Law.
</P>
<P>
China also continued cutting down on its textile, coal and
steel sectors, which are suffering from an oversupply in the face
of slackening market demand.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May period, China destroyed 1.15 million textile
spindles and resettled about 400,000 workers. The country also
closed down over 23,000 small coal mines, reducing the coal output
by 100 million tons, said an official of the State Economic and
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
During the period, bankruptcy was introduced to small oil
refinery, fire-powered power plants, and glass, cement and steel
works.
</P>
<P>
To improve management of state-owned enterprises (SOEs), the
commission has also held five management training sessions for
leading officials of 1,070 loss-making SOEs.
</P>
<P>
To date one-third of the major leaders of loss-making firms
have sat in for the management crack courses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
