<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Has Highest Living Standard in South Asia: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka boasts the highest
standard of living in South Asia, according to the latest Human
Development Index Report by the United Nation's Development
Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
This year's UNDP survey, like its predecessors, ranked 174
nations according to how people live, factoring in health care,
life expectancy, educational attainments and adjusted real income.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been placed in the medium development category
and ranked the 90th among 174 nations graded by the UNDP, ahead of
the Maldives (93), India (132), Pakistan (138), Nepal (144),
Bhutan (145) and Bangladesh (150).
</P>
<P>
The report said that Sri Lanka outranks all other South Asian
countries with a higher standard of living despite a crippling
16-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
India has for the first time moved into the medium development
category with an improvement of six points since the last
assessment by the UNDP.
</P>
<P>
Besides, in a study called "Exploring Sri Lanka's
Competitiveness", the United States Agency for International
Development said that Sri Lanka has received a score of 80 out of
100 for its economic performance and has been placed 20th out of
120 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
