<HEADLINE> Cuba Hails Venezuela's Decision to Extend Oil Trade Privileges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cuban Foreign Minister
Felipe Perez Roque on Tuesday praised Venezuela for deciding to
extend oil trade privileges to more Caribbean countries,
including Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Perez Roque, who is on a two-day visit to Venezuela, made the
statement at a joint press conference held at the Venezuelan
Foreign Ministry after signing several agreements on bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The extension will permit Cuba to have access to a line of
credit for oil purchase.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez last week pledged to extend
the San Jose agreement, which Venezuela and Mexico have maintained
since 1980 to supply both petroleum and its derivatives to a
number of Central American and Caribbean countries financed by
credit lines.
</P>
<P>
Among the beneficiaries of the San Jose agreement are Barbados,
Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, Haiti, Honduras, Jamaica,
Nicaragua and Panama.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Perez Roque and his Venezuelan counterpart Jose
Vicente Rangel signed an agreement on meteorology, an agreement on
judicial assistance in penal matters, the final act of the Mixed
Commission on Venezuelan-Cuban cooperation, and the act of the
sixth Summit of the Political Consultation Mechanism between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Perez Roque will wind up the first official visit
abroad since he was appointed as foreign minister last May.
</P>
