<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs 114.6 Billion Dollars in Next 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will require investments
estimated at 802.2 trillion rupiah (about 114.6 billion U.S.
dollars) over the next five years to boost economic growth, an
investment official said.
</P>
<P>
Soenaryo Dasusaputro, assistant for policy and investment
climate affairs to the investment minister, said the estimate was
based on the country's annual economic growth rate over the next
five years which would range between minus 2 percent and 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the country's economic growth rate would
be minus 2 percent in 2000, nil percent in 2001, 3 percent in
2002, and 5 percent respectively in 2003 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the investment projection, a number of investment
strategies and policies would be needed, Soenaryo said at an
investment consultation meeting in Padang, capital of West
Sumatera, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had already taken a number of bold
measures to lure investors, including the issuance of reform
policy packages in the investment sector aimed at restoring
business people's confidence in the country's business potentials.
</P>
<P>
To improve transparency in investment policies and ensure
business certainty, the government has also issued a presidential
decree on the negative list of investment.
</P>
<P>
"Under the presidential decree, there are fewer economic
sectors closed to foreign investors compared to the situation in
1995," the Antara News Agency Wednesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Industry and Trade Rahardi Ramelan
Tuesday told members of Commission V of the House of
Representatives in a hearing here that investors have not shown
strong interest in Indonesia despite the relatively stable
situation, the strengthening of the rupiah and the drop in bank
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"I think investors are still adopting a wait-and-see attitude
until the formation of a new government in Indonesia," Ramelan
said.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the Investment Coordinating Board
(BKPM), foreign direct investment approved by the Indonesian
government in the first six months of this year plunged by 77.5
percent to 1.88 billion U.S. dollars, from 8.35 billion dollars
during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Although the general picture of investment in Indonesia was
still not encouraging, Ramelan said that investment was taking
place in certain sectors, for example, the chemical, forestry and
agro-industries.
</P>
<P>
"There are developments in investment in the forestry and
agro-industries in the first three months of 1999, especially
those based on fishery, milk, bottled drinking water, tobacco
processing, and in downstream forestry industries like the
furniture industry," The Indonesian Observer Wednesday quoted
Ramelan as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
