<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Slips Down World-Wide Human Development Scale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Colombia descended from
the 53rd position to the 57th on the world-wide scale of human
development, due to its internal armed conflict and economic
crisis, said the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the economic crunches and internal wars, the
spread of the deadly disease AIDS also hindered the development of
the Colombian population, the UNDP said in a statement about human
development.
</P>
<P>
But the fall of four places on the scale does not necessarily
mean a general deterioration of the quality of life, added the U.N.
agency.
</P>
<P>
It attributed Colombia's down-sliding in the classification
mainly to its application of a new method to measure the Index of
Human Development (IDH), which takes into consideration the
effects of internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Two of the fundamental indexes, on which the classification is
based, show slight improvement. Life span rose from 70.3 years in
1997 to 70.4 a year later, and the annual income per capita from 6,
347 U.S. dollars to 6,810 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The index of literacy in Colombia suffered a slight fall, from
91.3 per cent to 90 percent in the adult population.
</P>
<P>
Another worrying indicator in the country's human development
is that the percentage of the Colombian population, which is not
expected to reach the age of 40 due to poverty, rose from 9 to 10.
1 percent, the UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
In Latin America, Colombia stayed within the top 10 countries
with the most advanced human development, above Cuba and Brazil,
but behind Chile, Argentina, Uruguay, Costa Rica, Venezuela,
Panama and Mexico.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
