<HEADLINE> Philippine Volcano Evacuees Suffer From Food Poisoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen evacuees from Mt. Mayon of
the Philippines have suffered from food poisoning after eating
foreign-donated relief goods from the Department of Social Welfare
and Development, the Today newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The evacuees at a relocation center in Albay were rushed to a
local clinic after suffering loose bowels and nausea when they ate
imported canned food and powered milk.
</P>
<P>
"The explosion (food poisoning) was as if under Alert Level 5
of the volcano," one of the victims, Domingo Banzuela, a retired
public school principal, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Banzuela suffered the disorder after drinking a glass of
imported milk that was included in the relief goods distributed by
the provincial social welfare official.
</P>
<P>
The relief goods consist of 20 boxes of chili and beans, which
also have caused stomach disorder among the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
As the victims were being treated for food poisoning, the
Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs)
raised the alert level to 3 around Mayon, which turned out to be a
false alarm causing greater panic among the villagers there.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of villagers living on the slopes of the active Mayon
Volcano were reportedly preparing for evacuation after the release
of the higher alert level, but the Phivolcs corrected its error in
data interpretation two hours later.
</P>
<P>
Alert Level 2 is still in effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
