<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossils of Stegodon Discovered in SW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Fossils of stegodon, an extinct
genus of early elephant dating back three million to eight million
years, have been discovered in the outskirts of Kunming, capital
of Yunnan Province in southwest China, scientists said here today.
</P>
<P>
The fossils, discovered in the area for the first time, were
found a few days ago by workers of a local brickyard while they
were digging with a bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
The fossils already unearthed include a two-meter-long ivory
and a skull with molars preserved completely, and further
excavation is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that the discovery will greatly help them
study the development of the Dianchi Lake and the ancient
environment, climate and geography around Kunming.  
</P>
</TEXT>
