<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Give SEA Games Athletes Doping Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports
Council (KONI) has announced it will hold pre-competition doping
tests for selected members of the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games
contingent, The Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National training director Imron ZS said the pre-competition
tests next week were aimed at reducing any possible problems at
the August 7 to 15 biennial event.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to take any risks by sending athletes who might
fail the doping test. We prefer to be a 'clean' contingent rather
than an overall champion with athletes found guilty of using
banned substances," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta doping laboratory located in Rawasari, Central
Jakarta, has offered to hold the pre-competition testing at no
cost to KONI.
</P>
<P>
Imron said he would recommend athletes not to consume any
medications without first consulting the official team doctor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's men's cyclist Tonton Susanto was found guilty of
using amphetamines during the 19th SEA Games here two years ago.
He was banned from national and international tournaments for
approximately one year.
</P>
<P>
KONI's chief of Sports Science Commission Carmen Jahya said she
would consult the contingent's four supervisors before selecting
athletes to undergo the test.
</P>
<P>
Carmen said three women's shooters, who left for Brunei
Darussalam in early July for pre-competition training and
acclimatization would not be tested.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian sporting delegation for the SEA Games plans to
visit President B.J. Habibie for a farewell ceremony ahead of
their departure to Brunei.
</P>
<P>
However, Imron has yet to confirm the date.
</P>
<P>
"It's either July 22 or 23. We're still waiting for a fixed
date from the State Secretariat," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will compete in 20 events at the biennial event with
a 392-strong contingent including officials. The contingent won't
leave on the same date of flight.
</P>
<P>
The cycling, shooting and football squads will fly earlier than
August 3 when the main group is scheduled to leave.
</P>
<P>
Imron met KONI chairman Wismoyo Arismunandar Tuesday to report
over the latest development of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
"The national camp has gone well. The athletes are all in good
physical shape. None of them have been injured ahead of their
departure," he said. 
</P>
