<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sees 17-Percent Rise In Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's economic
powerhouse, saw a year-on-year 17.7 percent rise in exports in the
first half of 1999, according to latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
Total exports amounted to 8.035 billion US dollars in the
period, announced Shanghai Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Commission, which attributed the increase to a surge in exports of
machinery and electrical products.
</P>
<P>
However, exports by local state-run foreign trade enterprises
were still stagnant, in sharp contrast to overseas-funded firms,
which contributed remarkably to the city's export growth.
</P>
<P>
During the January-May period, Shanghai exports were one
billion US dollars more than the same 1998 period, of which 996
million US dollars were brought in by overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Exports of machinery and electrical products were on a rapid
rise and accounted for nearly half of total exports during the
half-year period, and exports to Asia, Europe and North America
grew by two-digits.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai intends to maintain a 10-percent rise in exports in
the second half of the year and has set a goal to garner a total
of 17.6 billion dollars exports for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
The city will increase exports of hi-tech and hi-value-added
products and will also make good use of the marketing mechanism of
international chain enterprises to improve the presence and image
of local name-brand products in overseas markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
