<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medicines Reserved for Flood Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central China
has kept in reserve 30 million yuan worth of medicines, necessary
medical equipment and funds in preparation for this year's flood
control efforts, according to the provincial administration of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
China has introduced a medicine reserve system since the latter
half of 1998 to ensure sufficient supply at a time of natural
disasters or other accidents.
</P>
<P>
Hunan, located at the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, the
country's longest, is a disaster-prone region. It reserved 20
million yuan worth of medicines last year and another 10 million
yuan worth before the start of this year's flood season.
</P>
<P>
The reserves, which consist of Western medicine, ready-made
traditional Chinese medicines, medicinal raw materials, and
medical equipment, are placed at five medicine companies of the
province.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, flooding caused by heavy
rainfall along the Yangtze River Valley since late June has killed
more than 200 people and posed a threat to the lives of 60 million
local people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
