<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Province Breeding New Potato </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in northwest China's
Qinghai Province have developed a technique to prevent the growth
of potato virus by a process of detoxification in the course of
breeding.
</P>
<P>
With equipment provided by the European Union, scientists at
the Qinghai Academy of Agriculture and Forestry (QAAF) placed
detoxified potato shoots in a laboratory for cultivation. They
then transplanted these young shoots in a glass room where the
temperature, humidity, and sunlight were entirely controlled by
computers. When the potato stock was fostered to the fifth
generation, it was ready to be used for cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Sowing with these young shoots will not only curb the growth of
virus, but also increase potato output by 100 percent compared
with ordinary seedlings, said Wang Jian, head of QAAF's Biological
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
To date, this technique has been applied in 20 townships in
Qinghai, yielding 130 million yuan in profit for local farmers.
</P>
<P>
A staple food in China, the potato is grown on 34 million
hectares of land across the country each year. Qinghai is an ideal
place for growing potatoes since it is located in a frigid zone
with sharp variations in temperature between day and night, making
it difficult for insects to survive in the area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
