<HEADLINE> Famous South China Port to Undergo Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Humen, a township-level port of
Dongguan City in south China's Guangdong Province, will build two
new cargo berths and complete a number of other supporting
projects over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Humen is known as the place where Lin Zexu, the imperial high
commissioner of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) for suppression of
the opium trade, confiscated 20,283 chests and 2,000 bags of opium
from European and American merchants and burned them and flushed
them into the sea on June 3, 1839.
</P>
<P>
Present-day Humen is a township leading the way in economic
progress, and is home to 1,400 overseas-financed businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, a 4.5-km-long ring road, an 8-km-
long road from Nanshan to the port area, and a bridge and dredged
waterway will also be completed in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The township will also make efforts to explore the service
trades, boost the garment market, and organize a number of
international fairs to attract overseas investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
