<HEADLINE> Talks Between Costa Rica, Nicaragua Come to Standstill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations between Costa Rica
and Nicaragua to find a solution to various disagreements between
them "are at a standstill," said Costa Rican Vice President Walter
Niehaus on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between their two vice-presidents, initially planned
for this month, has been postponed indefinitely after a rise of
tensions in their relations, he said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agenda includes discussion on the navigation rights
on the border river of San Juan which have affected the bilateral
relations since last year.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua, which holds sovereignty over the river, banned the
transit of armed police from Costa Rica along the waterway, while
Costa Rica accused the ban as an infringement on its navigation
rights granted by treaties.
</P>
<P>
Another issue on the agenda is the Nicaraguans who are living
and working in Costa Rica illegally, whose number is believed by
Costa Rica to reach as many as 600,000.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government granted a six-month amnesty period
to all the Central American immigrants from February to November
9th.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman requested Costa Rica to
extend the initial term.
</P>
<P>
The immigrant situation took a turn for the worse, when two
weeks ago, the Costa Rican authorities deported almost 30 heads of
families, who had participated in the occupation of urban land
plots in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Nicaraguan congress sent a delegation to
investigate whether or not the Nicaraguan's rights were being
respected within Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
