<HEADLINE> Colombian Army Continues Fighting Against FARC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Colombian Army continued
Tuesday its fighting against the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC) which began on Saturday, and the death toll has
kept rising.
</P>
<P>
Armed forces chief General Fernando Tapias on Tuesday revealed
that specialized battalions were being sent to Puerto Rico, where
three policemen were killed in a clash with the FARC, that
launched a 12-hour attack on the municipal of Cucutilla, kidnapped
27 policemen and destroyed totally the police headquarters with
explosives made from adapted domestic gas cartridges.
</P>
<P>
In the Tuesday clash 36 were added to the death list of 242
rebels delivered on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Police chief General Rosso Jose Serrano said the search
continued for the remains of other possible victims below the
ruins.
</P>
<P>
Isolated attacks in various parts of the country, including
Santander North, Caqueta and Narino, and Risaralda are carried out
by the FARC rebels.
</P>
<P>
Both Tapias and Serrano said that El Doncello was under control
following the rebel's Saturday attack, which killed two children.
</P>
<P>
But the army denied that Florencia, capital of Caqueta, is
seized by the guerrillas, saying that the city is watched from
helicopters, and the guerrillas are trying to block the access
highways into the city.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between Colombian armed forces and the FARC began
on Saturday, just 10 days before peace talks between the
government and the rebels is due to resume.
</P>
<P>
President Andres Pastrana so far has made no official comment
on the fighting, but there was no suggestion that the July 20
peace talks would be delayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
