<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake of 5.3 degrees
on the Richter scale rock the south-east of Mexico, Guatemala and
El Salvador on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico, the earthquake affected Chiapas at 08:04 a.m. local
time (13:04 GMT) while in Guatemala it followed the Sunday tremor
that left at least one people dead and 37 others injured.
</P>
<P>
The National Seismological Service of Mexico placed the
epicenter on the Chiapas-Guatemalan border. But the Geotecnicas
Investigation Center in El Salvador said it was on the Guatemalan
coast.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala's Red Cross society, firefighters and the National
Coordination Committee for the Reduction of Disasters (CONRED)
still remained in a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
Escuintla, 57 kilometers southeast of the Guatemalan capital,
bore the brunt from the quake. 
