<HEADLINE> EU Official Urges Reform of Italy's Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Mario Monti, Italy's European
Commissioner for Competition, Tuesday called for a far-reaching
reform of the pension system and the removal of obstacles to an
efficient economy in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Mario Monti told the Italian Parliament that he agreed with the
European Central Bank, which called on Italy Monday to reform its
pension system and on France and Germany to review key aspects of
theirs.
</P>
<P>
He called for a far-reaching reform that solves the problem
once and for all, saying the key issue is to remove the "perennial
state of uncertainty" surrounding future pensions.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said measures are also needed to reduce
subsidies to industry, amend the rigid rules on skill-oriented
professions, further liberalize trade and credit, and intensify
the battle against tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The Italian pension system was partially reformed in 1993 and
1995 and is due for further revision in 2001. However, the reform
is strongly opposed by trade unions, and the government has not
yet made any progress in winning the unions' consent to some
pension moves in the next budget. 
</P>
