<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Includes "Non-nuclear" Clause Into Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Austrian parliament on Tuesday
passed a bill affirming that Austria will be a non-nuclear country.
The bill will be included into the constitution.
</P>
<P>
All the five parties in the parliament supported the bill which
bans the building of nuclear power plants and the storage of
nuclear weapons on Austrian territory.
</P>
<P>
Peter Kostelka, leader of the ruling Social Democratic Party's
parliamentary group, said in the parliament session that Austria
is the first and only European country whose constitution
prescribes the country to be non-nuclear.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Khol, leader of the parliamentary group of another
ruling party, the Austrian People's Party, also said in the
session that nuclear weapons in the world have been cut down by
two-thirds and the world in the future must be a non-nuclear one.
</P>
<P>
Austria built a nuclear power plant in 1978, but Austrians
voted against its use a referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
