<HEADLINE> U.S. Chamber of Commerce Delegation Starts Cuba Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce arrived here Tuesday on what it calls "a fact-finding
visit" to learn more about Cuba's economy.
</P>
<P>
President and chief executive officer of the Chamber of
Commerce, Thomas Donohue, who heads the delegation, is expected to
sign an accord of understanding with the Cuban Chamber of Commerce
before winding up the tour on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce opposes the trade embargo against
Cuba maintained by the Clinton administration. This trip was
licensed by the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is scheduled to meet with Cuban Parliament
President Ricardo Alarcon, Public Health Minister Carlos Dotres
and visit the Genetic Engineering and Biologic Center of Carlos J.
Finlay Institute.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1912 and with some 200,000 members, the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce is the largest of its kind in the world. It is
also an association of some three million business and
professional organizations. 
</P>
