<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Finance Population Project in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has agreed to
grant 250,000 U.S. dollars to Nicaragua over the next three years
to implement its population policies, a senior Nicaraguan official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be earmarked to help establish a system of
coordination, monitoring and evaluation of the country's
population policies, in addition to a plan of action, said
External Cooperation Secretary David Robleto.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan population is almost 5 million, with the life
expectancy rising from 44 to 66 years during the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
But what worries the authorities is that half of the population
live in poverty and one fifth in extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
One of the general goals of the population policies is to
contribute to the creation of demographic conditions favorable to
the social and economic development of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Edible Cactus Successfully Grown in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- An edible cactus introduced from
Mexico is growing well in China, and has recently been selling at
the vegetable stalls in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The cactus, called the Milpa Alta, was introduced to China last
year and can grow to the extent of 30,000 kilograms per hectare.
About seven hectares of the cactus is growing in Beijing and the
southernmost island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
Edible cactus cultivation has become a full-blown industry in
some countries of South America and Europe, with Mexico leading
the world in edible-cactus production.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that planting this cactus in China will not only
provide a new variety of vegetable, but also make it possible to
utilize large areas of arid and semi-arid land for agriculture
purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Rejects Amendments to N. Ireland Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Amendments designed by the
Protestant Ulster Unionist Party to save the Northern Ireland
peace process were rejected by the government in Britain's House
of Commons on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the Northern Ireland Bill, want guarantees
that Sinn Fein will be excluded from a proposed Northern Ireland
government if their military wing, the Irish republic Army (IRA)
do not hand in their weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionists said the legislation proposed by the
government was "flawed and unfair". Even with Britain's opposition
Conservative Party, they were unable to push through last-minute
changes to the legislation as it was rushed through parliament, a
Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
The amendments had sought to spell out more clearly that Sinn
Fein would be excluded from power if the IRA did not hand in
weapons according to a set timetable before a May 2000 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The government's emergency package was rushed through all its
stages in the House of Commons in eight hours of impassioned
debate Wednesday night.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Runner Takes Last Gold Medal in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya took its first and also
the last gold medal of the 20th Universiade which concluded here
Tuesday evening with a total of 146 gold medals offered in 12
sports.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Lagat displayed Kenya's dominance in the long-distance
event by taking the men's 1,500-meter final in 3:40.99, beating
Leszek Zblewski of Poland to second in 3:41.81 and Italian Lorenzo
Lazzari third in 3:42.36.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Kenya became the 28th country or region that harvest a
gold medal in the Palma Universiade.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the evening, Latvia also savored its first gold
medal in the Universiade when Eriks Rags threw to his winning
distance of 83.78 meters in his second attempt to take the men's
javelin title, beating Austrian Gregor Hoegler to second in 82.63
and Isbel Luaces of Cuba third in 82.18.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States still had the lion's share of four
out of the nine last gold medals from the track and field finals,
by sweeping all the men's and women's relay finals.
</P>
<P>
The American women quartets took the 4x100 and 4x400 meters
titles in 43.49 seconds and 3:27.97 respectively, while their men
compatriots triumphed in the 4x100 and 4x400 meters relays in 38.
55 and 3:00.88 respectively.
</P>
<P>
South Africa finished second in the men's 4x100 relay in 39.08,
beating Italy to third in 39.31 and Britain took the silver medal
in the men's 4x400 final in 3:03.95, with Senegal ranked third in
3:05.45.
</P>
<P>
The women's 4x100 relay silver medal went to Poland in 43.74
and Germany took the bronze medal in 43.96, as Russia ranked
second in the women's 4x400 relay in 3:30.54 and Britain in third
in 3:32.25.
</P>
<P>
The day's other three titles were split by Britain, Japan and
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Ben Challenger of Britain triumphed in the men's high jump with
an effort of 2.30 meters. Canadian Mark Boswell had to settle for
the silver medal although he also leapt to 2.30 meters as he only
succeeded in the 2.28 meters in his third effort whereas the
Briton made it in his second jump.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Lee Jin-Taek finished third in 2.28 meters.
</P>
<P>
Rie Ueno awarded Japan another athletics title by taking the
women's 5,000 meters in 15:51.24, beating Ana Dias of Portugal to
second in 15:53.23 and Romanian Cristina Casandra third in 16:03.
18.
</P>
<P>
Olena Shekhovisova of Ukraine triumphed in the women's long
jump with an effort of 6.92 meters in her second attempt, as
American Adrien Sawyer took the silver medal in 6.61 meters and
Maurren Maggi of Brazil finished third in 6.58 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
