<HEADLINE> High Quality Fields in Universiade with 10 Games Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The 20th Universiade was
marked by a very high sports and technical level that enhanced an
edition that celebrated the 50th anniversary of the International
University Sports Federation (FISU).
</P>
<P>
The Palma edition has attracted high quality participants like
Fu Minxia of China, the multiple Olympic champion, American
breaststroker Amanda Beard, the Olympic champion in 1996 and Anita
Nall, the Olympic champion in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In athletics, there was 200-meter specialist American John
Capel who run the 100-meters and finished second.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team presented very strong gymnasts led by Niemov,
Bondarenko and Kriukov, the men's team champions in the 1996
Olympics. Kriukov won two gold medals here and his female teammate
Khorkina, the world and Olympic champion, with four.
</P>
<P>
Other great recent world champions in gymnastics are Spanish
Jesus Carvalho and Romanian Marius Urzica who won the gold medal
in pommel horse.
</P>
<P>
From Cuba, there were great champions who all won a gold medal,
like famous judoda Driulis Gonzales, the Olympic champion in 1996
and triple jumper Yoelvis Quesada, the 800-meter specialist
Norbert Tellez and fencer Rolando Tucker.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss 800-meter European runner-up Andre Bucher also won
the same medal, and there are so many more like the attack of
Romanian women who won six gold medals in athletics, with three
games records.
</P>
<P>
The yachting competitions presented the world top 10 in men and
women 470 categories. In volleyball, Germany won with the
totality of their first-string men spikers, while the women's
diving has a field of more than 60 percent of the best world
caliber.
</P>
<P>
All the quality showed in the list of the new Universiade
records:
</P>
<P>
Swimming:
</P>
<P>
100m backstroke women: Norico Inada, Japan, 1:01.06
</P>
<P>
200m backstroke women: Miki Nakao, Japan, 2:10.32
</P>
<P>
4x100m medley women: Japan, 4:09.90
</P>
<P>
800m freestyle men: Mark Warkentin, United States, 8:00.81
</P>
<P>
Athletics:
</P>
<P>
400m hurdles women: Daymi Permia, Cuba, 53.95 and 54.57 (semi)
</P>
<P>
400m women: Ionela Pierlea, Romania, 49.88
</P>
<P>
Hammer women: Mihaela Melinte, Romania, 74.24 meters
</P>
<P>
Triple jump women: Adelina Gavrila, Romania, 14.33
</P>
<P>
5,000m men: Sergiy Lebed, Ukraine, 13:37.52
</P>
<P>
Shot pot men: Andrew Bloom, United States, 21.11 meters.
</P>
