<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer University Games Concludes in Palma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The 20th University Games
concluded here Tuesday evening with a record entry of athletes and
officials, and 10 games records set up in the fortnight sports
gala.
</P>
<P>
According to the International University Sports Federation (
FISU), a total of 6,009 participants from 125 countries and
regions showed up for the competitions started from July 2 to 13.
</P>
<P>
The previous record of 5,740 participants was set up at the
Fukuoka Universiade in 1995, in Japan with 3,949 athletes and 1,
791 officials.
</P>
<P>
For the Palma edition, a total of 4,076 athletes, including 1,
441 women, together with 1,933 officials were registered for the
12 sports of the athletics, basketball, diving, fencing,
gymnastics, judo, soccer, swimming, tennis, volleyball, water polo
and yachting.
</P>
<P>
Six athletics records and four swimming marks were broken in
the 20th Universiade, as both Romania and Japan shattered three
each, the United States beat two, with the other two under a Cuban
and a Ukrainian names.
</P>
<P>
From the swimming pool, Japanese Norico Inada broke the women's
100-meter backstroke in 1:01.06 and her teammate Miki Nakao
shattered the women's 200-meter backstroke in 2:10.32 before the
Japanese quartet surpassed the women's 4x00-meters medley in 4:09.
90 by Norico Inada, Kazue Nakashima, Tomoko Hagiwara and Naoko
Imoto.
</P>
<P>
American Mark Warkentin inked the new record in the men's 800-
meter freestyle in 8:00.81.
</P>
<P>
In the athletics competitions, Romania set three games records,
all by its women athletes as Ionela Tirlea claimed the 400-meter
title in 49.88 seconds, Adelina Gavrila triumphed in the triple
jump in 14.33 meters and Mihaela Melinte stood atop in the hammer
in 74.24 meters.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Daymi Permia beat the women's 400-meter hurdles in 53.95
seconds, while Sergiy Lebid of Ukraine took the men's 5,000 meters
in 13:37.52 and American Andrew Bloom reapt the shot put title in
21.11 meters.
</P>
<P>
The United States has the largest contigent with 380 members,
followed by the hosts Spain with 307. Japan sent in the third
greatest delegation of 282 members, as Russia fielded in 242
people, Italy with 228, Canada 218, and Ukraine 202.
</P>
<P>
Of the 146 gold medals offered at the Palma edition, the United
States topped the gold tally with 30, as Russia finished in a
distant second with 14, and Cuba in third with 12, one more than
Japan that bagged home 11.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Romania had nine golds apiece, with Spain and
Ukraine won seven each, followed by Italy and France, both with
six.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic and Poland had four each, followed by South
Korea with three.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Australia, Belarus, the Netherlands, Chinese Taipei,
Brazil, South Africa and Hungary, all won two gold medals apiece,
as eight countries scored their lone gold medal respectively,
namely Canada, Mexico, Belgium, Portugal, Mongolia, Latvia,
Britain and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In total, 29 countries and regions have produced their
champions in the Palma Universiade.
</P>
<P>
In two years time, the Summer Universiade will be organised in
Beijing, China, with table tennis and judo as optional sports.
</P>
<P>
In 2001, the Winter Universiade will go to Zakopane, Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
