<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved lower
Tuesday as investors were concerned with the possibility of a new
Latin American economy crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 25.96 at
11,175.02. The index rose 7.26 at the record closing high of
11,200.98 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 5.54 at 1,393.56 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 12.21 at 2,778.23.
</P>
<P>
The market fell after Argentine Presidential candidates hinted
at a possible moratorium on repayment of the country's debt
Monday. The hint pushed several Latin American markets lower on
that day but most stock market in the region bounced back Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 2.15 at 653.64 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.21 at 812.33. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.19 at 458.11.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,731 down, 1,281 up and 562
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 733.8 million shares from 668.9
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
