<DOCNO> XIE19990714.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Closes over 19 U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices surged to a new
20-month high on Tuesday after OPEC's leading producer Saudi
Arabia said it wanted to retain a tough line on export curbs.
</P>
<P>
London futures for benchmark Brent crude last traded 44 cents
higher to end at 19.04 U.S. dollars, breaching 19 U.S. dollars a
barrel for the first time since November 1997.
</P>
<P>
The latest leg to a rally which has nearly doubled oil prices
since February came after a Gulf official said Saudi Arabia wanted
cast iron proof of a full market recovery before the OPEC oil
cartel considered easing back export limits.
</P>
<P>
Speedy price gains since OPEC implemented curbs in April have
sparked debate about when the cartel should raise exports to stop
the market overheating.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that excess stockpiles are set to drain so
quickly over the next few months that inventories could be
depleted even before peak winter demand starts, according to a
Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
The output limits were set for a year until the end of March
2000 and last week two countries, Algeria and Iran, said they
wanted to retain the restrictions for the full term.
</P>
<P>
Traders on Tuesday also appeared to be anticipating fresh
evidence of a rundown in stockpiles in the important U.S. market
where weekly inventory data was due for release after the close of
the futures market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
